{[%evp 0,12,19,31,14,-14,43,38,37,33,33,39,37,19,15]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be3 {[#] The modern way of fighting King's Indian
Defence involves a little move h2-h3. Its idea is not just to protect
g4-square from ...Ng4 and ...Bg4 sorties, but also to prepare ambitious g2-g4
expansion. This can be a very effective prophylactic measure against Black's
typical kingside play, as well as a springboard to White's kingside attack(!)
- as discovered by the Soviet Grandmaster Vladimir Makogonov, after whom this
whole system was named.  White have traditionally used a combination of Ng1-f3
and h2-h3 on moves 5 and 6 to achieve this setup, which was investigated by
Grandmaster Mihail Marin in another Modern chess database.  The opening
repertoire that I present in this database is based on a clever move order
with Bc1-e3 and h2-h3 instead, which allows White to improve on several
important aspects of the move order with Nf3, while still achieving the same
strategic goals. By keeping the knight on g1, we keep flexibility on the
kingside, which is important for two reasons. Both of these reasons are
related to Black's most common response 6...e5 when we close the centre with
7.d5 and intend to follow it up with 8.g4, gaining space on the kingside and
fighting against Black's thematic ...f7-f5 break.  The first reason why it is
more flexible to play 6.Be3 instead of 6.Nf3 lies in Black's active option 7...
Nh5!? in that position. As we will see in the analysis section, while this is
a legitimately critical variation after the h3, Nf3 move order, it is not a
source of concern for White in a similar position after 6.Be3. This is a small,
but very important practical detail. The second reason why we keep the knight
'in the stable' for a while is that we can often execute Ng1-e2-g3 manoeuvre,
which is not available in case of 6.Nf3 when the knight is usually forced to
retreat to d2 to protect the e4-pawn. On g3, the knight is not only
more actively placed than on d2, but also facilitates the Saemisch attacking
setup with Be3, Qd2, h4-h5, etc. This is also an improvement over
the 6.Nf3 version of this variation. Is there any downside to this move order
if Black plays something else besides 6...e5? Well, strong Black players have
tried to prove that Be3 and/or h3 are not essential developing moves with 6...
c5, 6...Na6, 6...Nbd7, and 6...c6, but so far a clear antidote has not been
found - White usually gets a more pleasant position against all of these moves.
Below, I give an overview of the most common variations, classified by
chapters. You can find analysis of current opening theory, as well as many new
ideas, in individual chapters that follow. Throughout them, I will sometimes
refer to GM Marin's database on the Nf3 Makogonov variation, either for
comparison purposes or as reference material, since these two databases have
some complementary parts. Finally, you will be able to check your knowledge
and understanding of this system in the Test section of the database.} ({
In case of the traditional move order} 6. Nf3 e5 7. d5 {Black has an
additional option} Nh5 $5 {which, after} 8. g3 Na6 $5 {[#] can lead to quite
volatile positions once the position opens up after the inevitable ...f5, exf5,
gxf5. While probably still somewhat better, White is not as much in control
here as in positions with closed centre when he pushes g2-g4 quickly. Here are
two good examples of what typically happens is this variation:} 9. Be3 (9. Be2
f5 10. exf5 gxf5 11. Bg5 Nf6 12. Nh4 Qe8 13. Qc2 Nb4 14. Qd2 a5 15. a3 Na6 16.
Qc2 Nc5 $13 {1-0 (34) Gupta,A (2629)-Shabalov,A (2522) Hoogeveen 2015}) 9... f5
10. exf5 gxf5 11. Ng5 Nf6 12. Qd2 Nc5 13. O-O-O h6 14. Nf3 Nfe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4
16. Qc2 c6 $13 {1/2-1/2 (37) Rodshtein,M (2688)-Iniyan,P (2460) Teplice 2018})
6... e5 {This is Black's main response and it is studied in depth in the first
three chapters.} ({The second most popular option is, logically, another
attack on white centre with} 6... c5 {[#] White has two options here. The most
flexible continuation is} 7. Nf3 {keeping central tension.} ({Fans of Benoni
structure with White will be happy to learn that} 7. d5 {is quite playable
here, as well, and will be discussed in a separate chapter (Chapter 7).  Now,
the most common reply is} e6 ({while Benko-inspired} 7... b5 8. cxb5 a6 {
has not fared well for Black after} 9. a4 Qa5 10. Bd2 $1 $14) {After} 8. Bd3
exd5 9. exd5 {[#] two critical lines seem to be} {1)} Re8 {which transposes
into one of the well-known variations of the h3, Bd3 Benoni} ({and 2)} 9... Na6
10. Nf3 Nb4 {which is well met by:} 11. Be2 $1 Bf5 12. Rc1 Ne4 13. g4 $1 {
and White gets the upper hand in the arising complications.}) {after} 10. Nf3 {
According to the current opening theory, White has an edge in this variation. For
example, after the most popular move} Bh6 11. O-O Bxe3 12. fxe3 {White's
initiative on the f-file often proves to be unpleasant for Black.}) ({Black is
fine after} 7. dxc5 Qa5 $1 8. Bd3 dxc5 $11) {Black usually releases the
tension immediately with} 7... cxd4 ({Alternatives such as} 7... Qa5) ({and} 
7... Na6 {also deserve attention, and are the subject of Chapter 6.}) 8. Nxd4 {
[#] In this Maroczy-bind structure, Black has two different ways to challenge
White's setup. The more ambitious of the two is} b6 {developing in the
Hedgehog style.} ({A more classical approach is} 8... Nc6 {which transposes
into one of the topical variations of the Accelerated Dragon/Maroczy Bind after
} 9. Be2 Bd7 10. O-O Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. Qc2 {[#] As a matter of fact, White
has enjoyed great success with it (75%!) over the last several years, putting
a big question mark over the soundness of the whole system for Black - as we
will see in Chapter 5.}) {Here, it seems like Black can get a good game if
White castles kingside and is forced to defend his e4-pawn with f2-f3,
conceding weaknesses on dark squares around the king. However, I believe that
White should play more ambitiously:} 9. Qd2 $1 Bb7 10. f3 {[#] preparing to
castle queenside and attack with Be3-h6, h3-h4-h5, etc. The arising positions
are double-edged, but we will see in Chapter 4 that White's attack is quite
promising.}) ({In Chapter 8, we analyze a flexible setup with} 6... Na6 7. g4 {
This is the most consistent reply,} ({since} 7. Nf3 {would allow Black to
transpose to the h3, Nf3 variation after} e5 8. d5 Nh5 $5) {and now} 7... c6 $5
{[#] gives Black several options in the centre, including ...e7-e5, ...Na6-c7
and ...b7-b5, and even ...d6-d5. White has to play carefully over the next
several moves if he wants to get something tangible out of this position.}) ({
Black can try to be even more clever with his move order by starting with} 6...
c6 {when 7.g4 is not so good any more, so White should continue} 7. Nf3 {
[#] Some strong GMs have tried to take advantage of White's last move by
continuing} Na6 {and preparing 8...e5 9.d5 Nh5!? - trying to use the position
of the knight on f3 to their advantage, as discussed in a similar position
after 6...e5. However, White has a way to throw spanner in the works:} 8. Rc1
$1 {[#] This semi-waiting move has a deep tactical idea that is revealed only
a few moves later} ({In case of the 'natural' continuation} 8. Be2 {Black
obtains good counterplay with} e5 9. d5 Nh5 10. g3 cxd5 11. cxd5 f5 $1 12. exf5
gxf5 $132) 8... e5 9. d5 Nh5 {and now White can curb Black's kingside play
with:} 10. Nd2 Qe8 11. c5 $1 {when opening of the centre is in his favour. This
interesting variation is covered in Chapter 9.}) ({A more modest knight
development} 6... Nbd7 {is usually not challenging for White and he can
continue developing with} 7. Nf3 {Here, besides 7...e5 that usually transposes
to a favourable version of Nf3, h3 Makogonov for White after 8.d5 Nc5 9.Nd2 (as
discussed by Mihail Marin in his Makogonov database), Black also has a tricky
idea} a6 $5 {[#] preparing flank diversion 8...c5 9.d5 b5! White can meet this
in two good ways:} 8. Be2 ({and possibly even more precise} 8. Qc2 $5 {which
was played in only one game, but completely takes the sting out of ...b7-b5
after} c5 9. d5 {as e4-pawn is now defended.}) 8... c5 9. O-O ({Black's idea
can be seen in the variation:} 9. d5 $6 b5 10. cxb5 axb5 11. Bxb5 Nxe4 12. Nxe4
Qa5+ $17) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 {[#] with a Hedgehog-like position in which White
has a new idea to obtain an advantage out of the opening - explained in
Chapter 10.}) ({Finally, in Chapter 11 we look at some rare sidelines, such as
} 6... a6 7. Nf3 c6 {[#] which can be met well in more than one way. My
suggestions are} 8. Bd3 ({and} 8. c5)) ({and provocative} 6... Nc6 7. d5 Nb4 (
7... Nb8) ({or} 7... Ne5) 8. Nf3 e6 {[#] which is not so bad as it may seem at
 first glance since Black can have a decent shot at counter-attacking
white centre with moves like Rf8-e8, ...Nb4-Na6-c5, and ...c7-c6. This
variation is also discussed in the last chapter.}) 7. d5 {[#] In this typical
King's Indian pawn structure with a blocked centre, both sides try to develop
their play on the flanks as quickly as possible. Interestingly, in this
variation, it is often White, not Black, who takes the initiative on the
kingside.  Black's most common reply is} a5 {taking control of b4-square and
preparing knight manoeuvre to c5.} ({As explained in the introduction, an
attempt to start kingside play with} 7... Nh5 {[#] is not as strong here as in
6.Nf3 variation, in the view of:} 8. Be2 $1 Nf4 9. Bf3 f5 10. g3 {and Black is
forced to play} fxe4 11. Nxe4 $14 {when White obtains an outpost on e4 and
keeps a stable positional advantage. If we compare it to 7...Nh5 in 6.Nf3
variation, we see that Black's dynamic possibilities in the centre are quite
limited in this case.}) ({A serious alternative to 7...a5 is} 7... Na6 {
[#] (covered in Chapter 3), which is an attempt to save some time by omitting
the pawn move and just getting the knight to c5 as soon as possible. The game
usually continues along the similar lines as in 7...a5:} 8. g4 Nc5 9. f3 c6 (
9... h5 $5 {is an interesting sideline played by KID expert Gawain Jones
against Fabiano Caruana.}) 10. Nge2 cxd5 11. cxd5 Bd7 12. Ng3 {[#] and we have
reached a critical position where Black can either continue developing
queenside play with} Rc8 ({or create tension on the kingside with} 12... h5 $5)
) {Now, White continues his natural strategy with} 8. g4 {which not only
serves to fight against Black's ...f7-f5 break but also spearheads White's
potential kingside attack. After} Na6 {we see the second benefit of the move
order with early Be3 - White can develop the knight to} 9. Nge2 Nc5 {This is
the most popular, though perhaps not the best continuation, and it is studied
in Chapter 1.} ({The main alternative is} 9... Nd7 $5 {[#] preferred by top
GMs Nakamura and McShane, as well as some KID experts. Black prepares the
standard knight manoeuvre toward the queenside, as well as the ...f7-f5 break.
After:} 10. Qd2 Ndc5 11. Ng3 c6 12. Be2 cxd5 {[#] we get an important moment,
studied in detail in Chapter 2 when all three recaptures are possible.} 13.
cxd5 {is the most solid, keeping control of the centre, but also enabling
Black to develop queenside counterplay around ...b7-b5-b4.} (13. exd5 $5 {
is a more dynamic option, as it increases White's queenside control at the
expense of central control (Black can play ...f7-f5 and ...e5-e4). It often
leads to razor-sharp play in the middlegame.}) ({Finally,} 13. Nxd5 {keeps
both black breaks (...b7-b5 and ...f7-f5) in check, while also firmly
controlling d5-outpost. However, there is a significant downside to it as it
allows} Ne6 $132 {when Black gets access to important dark squares d4 and f4.})
) 10. Ng3 {basically shutting down ...f7-f5 forever, so Black has to turn to
queenside for counterplay:} c6 {and here White can set up a nice attacking
position with} 11. Qd2 (11. g5 {is another possibility, though Black can get
practical counterplay with the following pawn sacrifice:} Nfd7 $1 12. dxc6 bxc6
13. Qxd6 Ne6 $44 {followed by Nd4.}) 11... cxd5 12. cxd5 Bd7 13. f3 a4 14. h4
Qa5 15. h5 {[#] with excellent prospects on the kingside. Of course, Black has
many alternatives along the way, but this position (reached in several games
so far) shows White's basic plan. I am sure that such an aggressive setup
against the King's Indian Defence would appeal to many modern chess players!} *

