{[%evp 0,54,16,28,35,-11,54,35,24,37,32,43,28,15,12,9,52,11,5,-18,-18,-1,-18,
-19,19,18,19,15,26,-15,47,41,25,-5,63,44,49,70,37,50,46,9,64,66,71,57,67,68,70,
61,61,7,7,143,99,92,92]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6.
Be3 e5 7. d5 a5 8. g4 Na6 9. Nge2 ({The other move order with} 9. Qd2 $5 Nd7 {
just transposes to the corresponding variation in 9.Nge2 line after} 10. Nge2
Ndc5 11. Ng3 {-9.Nge2 Nd7}) 9... Nd7 10. Qd2 Ndc5 {[#] This manoeuvre is
considered to be the best way to meet the Makogonov with Nf3. As explained in
the introduction, things are a bit different here as white knight reaches a
more active g3-square, while the queen takes its place on d2, with attacking
intentions. Nevertheless, this might also be the most challenging Black's
response against Be3, h3 system - with one condition: if Black knows how!} 11.
Ng3 c6 12. Be2 {This developing move has been a unanimous choice of White
players.} ({However, it is somewhat surprising that no one has tried} 12. f3 $5
$146 {[#] yet (according to my database), especially since f2-f3 is played in
a similar position in 9...Nc5 variation. This move has an upside and a
downside. The upside is that it opens the second rank for the white queen to swing
to h2 with an attack. On the other hand, it weakens dark squares on the kingside,
which may be the reason why White had preferred 12.Be2 up to this point.
Nevertheless, I think that it is a worthy alternative, as can be seen from the
analysis below:} cxd5 13. cxd5 Bf6 $1 {[#] This is the most principled move
considering weakening of the dark squares. Yet, it may not be the most
intuitive response since it looks risky to provoke white pawns.} ({A more
natural continuation is} 13... f5 {but I think that White does not mind
opening of the position here:} 14. gxf5 gxf5 15. exf5 Qh4 (15... Bxf5 16. h4
Kh8 17. h5 $36 {looks more pleasant for White, although it is fairly complex.})
16. Qf2 Bxf5 17. Nxf5 Qxf2+ 18. Kxf2 Rxf5 19. Bxa6 $1 $14 {and after this
important exchange, White should have better chances in the endgame due to
control of the light squares and passive black bishop, no matter how Black
recaptures on a6.}) ({It is also important to note that the plan which works
well for Black in 12.Be2 variation is just too slow here due to:} 13... Bd7 14.
h4 Nc7 15. h5 b5 16. Qh2 $1 $40 {White does not have this attacking option in
case of 12.Be2. Black is already in trouble.}) 14. h4 $5 {This thematic pawn
sacrifice allows White to keep some initiative.} ({Instead,} 14. g5 {wins a
tempo, but loses the grip on f5-square, so Black's provocation on move 13
works out well after} Bg7 15. h4 f5 16. exf5 gxf5 $13 {with a complicated
position. Both sides have many options here. I guess that White can keep
things in control to some degree with:} 17. Bxa6 $5 Nxa6 18. f4 {but I would
not dare to say that he has any significant advantage.}) 14... Bxh4 15. Qh2
Bxg3+ 16. Qxg3 f6 {Opening the seventh rank for defense.} 17. O-O-O Rf7 18. Kb1
Bd7 19. Rd2 $44 {and White has obvious compensation thanks to attacking
potential on the h-file and a powerful dark-squared bishop. I prefer White's
position here, but I do not doubt that there are players who would not mind
playing this position with Black either.}) 12... cxd5 {[#] We have reached an
important crossroads for White. Normally, he recaptures on d5 with the c-pawn
almost automatically, but here he can recapture on d5 in three reasonable ways.
However, it has to be said immediately that the recapture with a piece on d5
is not principled because it grants black knight square e6 from where it can
target outposts on d4 and f4. Thus, the focus will be on two pawn recaptures:
13.cxd5 (more solid) and 13.exd5 (more dynamic).} 13. cxd5 ({The dynamic option
} 13. exd5 $5 {[#] is a new fashion. It was played by two strong GMs (Bluebaum,
Grandelius), so it definitely deserves our attention. Clearly, White
sacrifices his central control by transforming into a Sicilian type of pawn
structure. However, his pieces are placed very well for the inevitable opening
of the position. In two games that reached this position so far, Black has
chosen the straightforward} f5 ({However, I have to draw your attention to
another idea that still awaits practical tests:} 13... a4 $5 $146 14. h4 e4 $1
{[#] Black uses the combination of ...a4-a3 and ...Nc5-d3 threats to put white
under pressure and slow down his attack. This leads to very double-edged play.
I have analyzed the following variations:} 15. Rb1 {Escaping the gaze of
g7-bishop makes sense, although White has a few other options, too.} (15. h5 {
looks natural, but Black obtains excellent counterplay with} a3 $1 16. bxa3
Nd3+ 17. Kf1 Nac5 $132 {and if} 18. Ngxe4 {then} Nxe4 19. Nxe4 f5 $1 $17) ({
In the view of unpleasant check on d3 in some lines, another idea that
deserves attention is} 15. Kf1 $5 {which takes away this tactical possibility
from Black.} f5 16. gxf5 ({A direct attacking attempt} 16. h5 {is not
dangerous for Black:} a3 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. Rb1 axb2 19. Bd4 Bxd4 20. Qxd4 Qf6
21. Qxf6 Rxf6 22. Rxb2 Nc7 $11) 16... Bxf5 17. Nxf5 gxf5 ({Compared to a
similar position with 15.Rb1 instead of 15.Kf1,} 17... Rxf5 18. h5 $36 {
works better for White here.}) 18. Rg1 Qxh4 (18... Rf7 19. Bg5 Qf8 20. Bh5 Rd7
21. Ne2 $36) 19. Bh6 Rf7 20. Qf4 Qxf4 21. Bxf4 {and, once again, it is good to
compare this endgame to a similar one after 15.Rb1. White still has very good
compensation for the pawn, but here Black has an additional option} a3 $13 {
with a lively, but roughly balanced endgame.}) 15... f5 16. gxf5 Bxf5 17. Nxf5
{[#] Black has a choice between two recaptures.} Rxf5 (17... gxf5 {is more
risky as it gives White the initiative on the g-file:} 18. Rg1 Qxh4 19. Bh6 Rf7
20. Qf4 Qe7 ({After} 20... Qxf4 21. Bxf4 $36 {white keeps some initiative in
the endgame. He is also most likely getting his pawn back as d6 pawn is not
worth defending.}) 21. Bg5 Qf8 22. Nb5 $36 {White has more active pieces,
though the position remains double-edged.}) 18. h5 $13 {White is in time to
open the h-file and he should have his fair share of chances in
this double-edged affair. The position is quite complex and worth analyzing in-depth. Some possible variations are:} Qf6 (18... Nd3+ 19. Kf1 Nac5 20. Bg4 Qd7
$1 $44) 19. Kf1 Rf8 20. Bg4 Re5 $13) 14. gxf5 Bxf5 15. Nxf5 {There is nothing
wrong with this,} ({though White also has time for} 15. h4 $5 $146 {[#] Black
has no immediate threats, so I see no reason why White should rush the
exchange on f5. I analyzed two possibilities for Black:} Qc8 {preparing ...
Na6-b4-c2.} ({and:} 15... a4 16. h5 a3 17. bxa3 e4 18. Nxf5 Rxf5 19. hxg6 hxg6
20. Kf1 $1 Qf6 21. Rc1 Rf8 22. Bg4 $16) 16. h5 (16. f3 $5 {is also possible,
but more complex.}) 16... Nb4 17. Bxc5 Qxc5 18. Nxf5 gxf5 19. h6 {Played in
Alpha Zero style. Having a thorn on h6 can not hurt White's chances. But it
also allows him to activate his rook in an original way.} Bf6 20. Rh5 $1 Be7
21. Bf1 Kh8 22. O-O-O $14 {We got a very similar type of position to the one
that arises after the 16th move of 15.Nxf5 variation. This is clearly a better
version for White as black bishop is not on the long diagonal.}) 15... gxf5 16.
O-O-O {[#] Such positions with opposite-side castling are always very
double-edged. White attacks on the light squares and g-file, Black on the dark
squares and c-file.} Kh8 {This is more precise} ({than the immediate} 16... f4
17. Bxc5 Nxc5 18. Bd3 $14 {especially in connection with the following rushed
pawn sacrifice.} e4 $6 19. Bxe4 $1 Nxe4 (19... Bxc3 20. Qxc3 Nxe4 21. Rhg1+ {
is no good for Black.}) 20. Nxe4 Rc8 21. Qc2 Qd7 22. Rhg1 $18 {1-0 (33)
Bluebaum,M (2618)-Miller,E (2382) Magdeburg GER 2019}) 17. Rhg1 f4 18. Bxc5
Nxc5 19. Qc2 ({Bluebaum's} 19. Bd3 $5 {also looks fine.}) 19... e4 {Black is
running a risk of having his dark-squared bishop shut down forever should
White post a piece on e4.} ({Yet, he still had time to include} 19... a4 $1 {
and I believe that we get a critical position for this line after:} 20. Bd3 (
20. Ne4 f3 $1 21. Bd3 Nxe4 22. Bxe4 Rc8 $132) 20... e4 21. Bxe4 a3 22. b4 Nd7
$44 {with mutual chances.}) 20. Nxe4 Nxe4 21. Qxe4 Qf6 $44 {Black 
has compensation for the sacrificed pawn, but not more.} 22. Rd2 f3 23. Bd3 Qh6
{and here in the game Grandelius, N (2691)-McShane, L (2688) Eskilstuna SWE 2019
½-½ (50), White could have started successful regrouping with} 24. Qe1 $1 $14
