31,84,78,69,48,44,44,40,40,38,36,38,18,0,1,21,21,9,1,20,20,20,2]} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be3 e5 7. d5 Na6 {[#] As I already
explained in the introduction, this move promises Black quicker counterplay
than 7...a5. On the flip side, it allows White to expel the knight with b2-b4
at some point. Still, this is a rather double-edged move, requiring serious
committment from White since his king would then be left without the pawn
shelter on the queenside.} 8. g4 Nc5 ({Black tried something different than
the usual in the following game:} 8... c6 9. Nge2 cxd5 10. cxd5 b5 $6 {but
this active move is also quite weakening, and Nihal Sarin took advantage of it
skillfully:} 11. Ng3 b4 12. Nb5 $1 Nc5 13. Qc2 $16 {14.Nxd6 is in the air, so
Black decided to go for broke with:} Ncxe4 $6 14. Nxe4 Nxd5 {but after} 15.
Nbxd6 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Qh4+ 17. Qf2 Qe7 18. Bc4 $18 {he was completely lost in
Nihal,S (2598)-Gukesh,D (2533) Brest FRA 2019 1-0 (36)}) 9. f3 c6 ({An
interesting alternative} 9... h5 $5 {[#] was played by Gawain Jones against
Fabiano Caruana:} 10. Qd2 Nh7 {Black's idea is to prevent White's typical pawn
attack and, if allowed, establish a blockade on the dark-squares with ...h5-h4,
...Bg7-f6-g5, etc.} {Caruana played conservatively} 11. O-O-O {which is fine,}
({although it is worth looking into a more direct approach:} 11. b4 $5 $146 {
[#] As discussed in the introductory note, this is a rather committal move
considering that White is overextending his pawn structure and providing
targets for Black. Here, it seems to work well, though, as can be seen from
sample variations below.} Nd7 (11... Na6 12. a3 Nb8 (12... h4 13. c5 $16) {
And now White can open up the position on the kingside favourably with} 13. gxh5
$1 Qh4+ 14. Qf2 Qxh5 15. Nb5 Na6 16. Ne2 {when Black queen is placed quite
awkwardly, and may even get trapped after h3-h4 and Ne2-g3.} f5 17. Ng3 Qh4 18.
exf5 gxf5 19. O-O-O $1 $16 {and in this unusual position, White has a clear
advantage since his pieces are much better placed.}) 12. gxh5 $1 {Once again,
White should open some files on the kingside at once.} gxh5 13. O-O-O a5 14. b5
{Black has obtained an outpost on c5, but his other pieces are far from
ideally placed. Some possible lines are:} h4 (14... Nc5 15. h4 f5 16. Bh3 $16)
15. Bd3 Nc5 16. Bc2 Kh8 17. Nge2 $16 {[%cal Gf3f4]}) 11... h4 12. Bd3 (12. Nge2
$5 {looks more flexible, preparing f3-f4 break after Bf1-g2.}) 12... Nxd3+ 13.
Qxd3 f5 ({Black could have created tension on both sides of the board with} 
13... a6 $5 14. Nge2 b5 15. cxb5 axb5 16. a3 Bd7 17. Na2 f5 $132) 14. Rh2 {
Caruana continues with his conservative policy,} ({but he could have opened up
the game with} 14. gxf5 $5 gxf5 15. f4 $1 $36 {with a double-edged position in
which black king may feel more exposed along the g-file or a1-h8 diagonal
should White manage to trade dark-squared bishops.}) 14... Kh8 15. Rg2 Bd7 $6 {
[#] Jones underestimates the strategic dangers of having advanced h-pawn.} ({
He could have obtained a comfortable blockade with} 15... f4 16. Bf2 Bf6 17. c5
Qe7 $11) 16. exf5 $1 gxf5 17. g5 {Now the h4-pawn has been cut off.} f4 18. Bf2
Qe8 19. Ne4 $16 {Caruana-Jones,G, Wijk aan Zee 2018}) (9... Ne8 {preparing ...
f7-f5 has also been tried in practice. I think that the following game by GM
Lupulescu pretty much shuts down this line as a serious attempt by Black:} 10.
Qd2 f5 11. exf5 {White takes with this pawn first, so that ...f5-f4 woud not
be an issue on the next move.} gxf5 12. O-O-O a6 {preparing counterplay with ..
.b7-b5 makes sense.} (12... f4 $6 {gives up e4-square.} 13. Bxc5 dxc5 14. h4
Nd6 15. Nh3 $16) 13. gxf5 $1 {[#] Perfect timing to open the g-file.} Bxf5 (
13... Qh4 {stops White's plan in the game for one move, but misplaces the
queen. White has a convincing way to exploit this:} 14. Bg5 Qh5 15. h4 Bxf5 16.
b4 $1 Nd7 17. Nce2 $1 Qf7 18. Ng3 e4 19. Nxf5 Qxf5 20. f4 Nef6 21. Bh3 $16) 14.
h4 b5 15. h5 $1 {Preparing the following strong pawn sacrifice:} b4 16. Ne4
Nxe4 17. fxe4 Bxe4 18. Bg2 Bxg2 19. Qxg2 $40 {with a decisive attack.} Kh8 20.
h6 Bf6 21. Nh3 Qd7 22. Rhg1 Qa4 23. Rdf1 b3 24. axb3 Qxb3 25. Rxf6 $1 Qxe3+ 26.
Kc2 {1-0 (26) Lupulescu,C (2634)-Eminov,O (2274) Konya 2017}) (9... a5 {
is also played often in this position, though it transposes to Chapter 1.}) 10.
Qd2 ({Young Indian star Nihal Sarin tried the enterprising} 10. b4 $5 {and
after} cxd5 11. cxd5 (11. bxc5 $2 d4 $17) 11... Ncd7 {is perhaps not the
critical reply,} ({but rather} 11... Na6 $5 $146 {which wins a tempo for Black
to organize counterplay more quickly.} 12. a3 Ne8 13. h4 f5 $132 {and the
problem for White here is that he can not afford to open the center as in some
other lines.}) 12. Bd3 a5 13. a3 Ne8 {[#]} {Now, White should have kept the ...
f7-f5 break in check with} 14. Nge2 $146 ({Instead, in the game he went for} 
14. h4 $6 {but his opponent took the initiative with resolute play:} f5 $1 15.
gxf5 gxf5 16. h5 h6 17. Nge2 fxe4 18. Bxe4 Ndf6 19. Bg6 e4 $1 20. Nxe4 axb4 $13
{Nihal,S-Aryan,C, Xingtai 2019}) {and if} 14... Bh6 $5 {which was, presumably,
one of the main ideas behind the knight retreat,} 15. Bxh6 Qh4+ 16. Ng3 $1 Qxh6
17. Qd2 $14 {promises him a better endgame thanks to the weak d6-pawn.}) 10...
cxd5 11. cxd5 Bd7 12. Nge2 {[#]} (12. b4 {is perhaps slightly premature, since
after} Na4 13. Nxa4 Bxa4 14. Ne2 {instead of} a5 ({Black has at least two good
alternatives:} 14... Bd7 15. Ng3 Ne8 $132) ({and even} 14... Rc8 $5 {as in the
game Anton Guijarro-Chopra below.} 15. Nc3 Rxc3 $1 16. Qxc3 Nxd5 17. exd5 e4
$132) 15. bxa5 Qxa5 $2 {Going into the endgame is not a wise decision.} 16.
Qxa5 Rxa5 17. Nc3 Bd7 18. a4 Rc8 19. Ra3 $16 {0-1 (43) Bosiocic,M (2613)
-Gukesh, D (2536) Karlsruhe GER 2019}) {At this point, Black has tried two
moves in practice. Two KID specialists, GMs McShane and Demchenko, continued}
12... h5 {[#] looking to stop white kingside attack and possibly set up the
well-known dark-square blockade with ...h5-h4, ...Nf6-h7 and ...Bg7-f6-g5.} ({
However, I don't think that GM Chopra's flexible} 12... Rc8 {[#] is any worse.
Here, White has several options, and I believe that he should continue the
waiting game with} 13. Rc1 $5 $146 {until Black shows his cards.} ({Iturrizaga
played} 13. b4 Na4 14. Nxa4 Bxa4 15. Nc3 {but this is not too impressive in
the view of both} Bd7 ({and also} 15... Rxc3 $5 {leading into some tactical
complications:} 16. Qxc3 Nxd5 17. exd5 e4 18. Qa3 Bxa1 19. Qxa4 exf3 $44 {
and while the engine claims that this is 0.00, in such a position only one
mistake could decide the game in favour of one of the players.}) 16. Rc1 a6 17.
Be2 h5 {This plan will prove to be time-consuming in this position.} ({Simpler
was} 17... Ne8 18. O-O f5 $11) 18. a4 h4 $6 19. O-O Nh7 20. b5 $1 Qa5 21. Rc2
Bf6 22. Rfc1 $14 {and White had a slight initiative on the queenside, though
he did not manage to make much out of it. ½-½ (35) Anton Guijarro, D-Aryan, C
Moscow 2019}) (13. Ng3 {is also possible, though it is still not too late for
Black to play} h5 {After} 14. Rg1 (14. gxh5 $2 {does not work tactically:} Nxh5
15. Nxh5 Qh4+) 14... h4 15. Nh1 Nh7 16. Nf2 {we get a rather complex position
similar to those analyzed in 13.Rc1 variation, although I am not sure if the
time-consuming knight manoeuvre via h1 was worth it.}) {There is no practical
material here, so I analyzed some possible ways that the game could develop
over the next several moves. Generally, if White can trade off the strong
c5-knight and keep Black's attempts to create counterplay at bay, his space
advantage should give him better long term prospects.} 13... h5 (13... Ne8 14.
b4 Na6 (14... Na4 15. Nxa4 Rxc1+ 16. Qxc1 Bxa4 17. Nc3 Bd7 18. Kd2 $5 {This is
quite an unusual manoeuvre. White king will be safe on b2 or even b3 square!} f5
19. Kc2 $14) 15. a3 f5 16. gxf5 gxf5 17. h4 $14) (13... a5 14. Ng3 h5 15. Bb5
h4 16. Nge2 $14) 14. b4 Na4 15. Nxa4 Rxc1+ 16. Qxc1 Bxa4 17. Nc3 Bd7 18. Bd3
Nh7 19. Ke2 $14) 13. Nc1 {This is a logical manoeuvre to trade off the most
active black piece.} ({However, there is another way to do it:} 13. b4 $5 $146
Na4 14. Nxa4 Bxa4 15. Nc3 Bd7 {and now I like the following plan for White:}
16. a4 a6 17. O-O-O $5 {Somewhat unexpected, but the king will feel safe on
the queenside even with such advanced pawns as long as the centre is blocked.
Black simply does not have enough influence on that part of the board. For
example,} Nh7 18. Kb2 h4 19. Rg1 $14 {still gives White a more pleasant
position.}) 13... Nh7 ({In the most recent game,} 13... Rc8 {was played, and
now I see no reason why White would not play} 14. Nd3 $146 (14. Nb3 {is an
interesting way to execute this trade, but it did not impress in the game:}
Nxb3 15. axb3 a6 16. Bd3 Nh7 17. O-O-O h4 18. Kb1 $6 Bf6 $11 19. f4 exf4 20.
Bxf4 Re8 21. Rhf1 Be5 $132 {0-1 (65) Grandelius,N (2691)-McShane,L (2688)
Eskilstuna SWE 2019}) 14... Nxd3+ 15. Bxd3 a6 16. Rg1 b5 17. a3 Nh7 {[#] and,
once again, white king can find safety on the queenside:} 18. O-O-O $1 $14 a5
19. Kb1 b4 20. Nb5 $16 {and White controls the situation on both wings with
his active pieces.}) 14. Nd3 Nxd3+ 15. Bxd3 h4 {This logical sequence was
played in the game Santos Latasa-Demchenko, Tegernsee 2018, but now White made
a positional oversight that allowed Black to complete his strategy on the dark
squares. This could have been stopped simply with} 16. Rg1 $146 {and I believe
that White should keep a slight, but solid edge thanks to his space advantage.}
({In the game} 16. O-O $6 {was played, allowing Black to fully equalize with}
Bf6 17. Kh2 Bg5 $11) {One possible continuation is:} 16... a6 (16... Bf6 17. g5
{is the point, of course.}) 17. a3 b5 18. Nd1 {The knight will go to f2 and
later to g4 or d3.} Rc8 {and here I like the subtle move} 19. Ke2 $5 $14 {
preparing to meet} f6 {with} 20. Qe1 $1 *

