{[%evp 0,99,16,28,29,-16,43,46,54,60,38,37,43,17,38,12,16,7,34,2,-18,-8,-7,-6,
11,-3,15,-94,-47,-17,-52,-52,-56,-11,-30,-50,6,-19,89,-152,-103,-205,-180,-89,
-16,-16,10,-1,188,133,176,169,193,-1,172,230,237,234,259,240,283,245,242,268,
268,257,273,256,311,329,362,335,335,275,334,297,1401,2090,29991,29992,29993,
29990,29991,949,1194,1202,1242,557,748,535,620,624,624,625,625,629,672,672,721,
785,838,789]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be3 c5 7. Nf3
cxd4 8. Nxd4 {In this chapter, we explore Black's fianchetto Hedgehog setup
against Be3, h3 system. This is a fairly popular approach for Black since it
gives him a lot of flexibility if he does not mind giving up some space in
the centre, of course. One of the 'selling points' of the system is the issue
of dark squares should White defend the e4-pawn with f2-f3, which is normally
not the case in such structures as the pawn is usually on h2.} b6 ({Besides 8..
.b6, Black sometimes play} 8... a6 $5 {[#] keeping White guessing as to
whether he will still go for the Hedgehog setup or something else. While I
have not seen any strong player play like this, I think that White can
continue in the same aggressive way as against 8...b6 with} 9. Qd2 $146 ({
Naturally, the alternative} 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. f3 Nbd7 12. Qd2 {gives
White a reasonable position, but that would mean that Black has proven that 8..
.a6 is a more precise move order than 8...b6. White can at least try to
dispute this with the more ambitious 9.Qd2.}) 9... b6 ({There is no practical
material to confirm this, but perhaps Black's idea with this move order is to
launch a Benko-inspired pawn sacrifice:} 9... b5 $5 {[#]} 10. cxb5 Bb7 11. f3
d5 $1 {when White should indeed keep the centre closed due to Black's lead in
development:} 12. e5 Nh5 {and now I believe that the right move should be} 13.
bxa6 $1 ({Instead,} 13. f4 Ng3 14. Rg1 e6 $44 {gives Black the compensation
that he hoped for.}) 13... Nxa6 14. g4 Ng3 15. Bxa6 $1 {This intermediate move
was the point behind 13.bxa6. Now White can play against the misplaced
g3-knight.} Rxa6 ({The alternative is} 15... Bxa6 16. Rg1 Bxe5 17. Kf2 $1 Qd6
18. f4 Bxd4 19. Qxd4 Ne4+ 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Qxd6 exd6 $14 {and we get an
opposite-coloured bishops endgame with rooks on the board. I am not sure how
serious White's winning chances are here, but it is clear that he has the
upper hand due to control over dark squares and a more promising pair of
connected pawns.}) 16. Rg1 Bxe5 17. O-O-O $14 {and while the position is very
complicated, I would prefer White simply because Black has a bad piece on g3.})
10. f3 Bb7 {and now White can immediately start the action with:} 11. h4 $1
Nbd7 (11... h5 {[#] would be met with a thematic breakthrough sacrifice:} 12.
g4 $1 Nc6 (12... hxg4 13. h5 Nxh5 14. Nf5 $1 $40) 13. gxh5 Nxh5 14. O-O-O $40 {
and the black king is the more exposed one.}) 12. Bh6 Bxh6 13. Qxh6 e6 {
which transposes into the game Grandelius-Chigaev from 8...b6 line.}) 9. Qd2 {
This is the most principled way to meet Black's slightly passive system. White
just wants to attack as in the Dragon variation of the Sicilian Defence. The
only issue is that the c4-pawn may become a target for a counter-attack, making
white king slightly vulnerable on the queenside. Nevertheless, we will see
that White has a solution for that!} ({Most strong players prefer this
aggressive approach, though it has to be said that White also has two solid
positional alternatives in:} 9. g3 Bb7 10. Bg2 Nbd7 11. O-O Rb8 12. Qc2 a6 13.
Rad1 e6 14. Rfe1 Qe7 15. Qd2 Rfc8 16. b3 Ba8 $13 {Bluebaum-Amin, Wijk aan Zee
2018}) ({and:} 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. b3 Nc5 13. f3 a6 (13...
e6 14. Bb1 d5 $132) 14. Re1 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 h6 16. Nde2 Nd7 17. Bd4 Nc5 18. Qd2
Bxd4+ 19. Nxd4 $14 {Lupulescu-Fedorov,A, Batumi 2018}) 9... Bb7 10. f3 {
[#] White is getting ready for the classical kingside attack, so Black has to
quickly decide how to meet it. In practice, three different approaches were
tried:} Nc6 {This way, Black prevents 11.Bh6 that is possible in case of 10...
Nbd7.} (10... Nbd7 11. Bh6 $1 {[#] The exchange of dark-squared bishops
weakens the defence of black king and eliminates a potent attacking piece for
Black at the same time.} Bxh6 ({Black tried to obtain quick counterplay in the
centre in the following game:} 11... e6 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. O-O-O d5 14. exd5
exd5 {but this did not bring him anything good after:} 15. h4 $40 h5 16. Qg5 ({
The engine indicates a beautiful forced win for White:} 16. g4 $1 hxg4 17. h5
Rh8 18. Bd3 $1 Rxh5 19. Bxg6 $1 Kxg6 20. Nce2 $1 $18) 16... Re8 17. Bd3 Ne5 18.
Bc2 Nh7 19. Qxd8 Raxd8 20. cxd5 $16 {Svane-Kovalev,V, Moscow 2019}) 12. Qxh6 e6
({In the game Kulaots-Sepp, Finland 2019, White built up a strong attacking
position after:} 12... Rc8 13. h4 Ne5 14. h5 $40 Qd7 15. O-O-O $1 Nxc4 16. g4
e6 {and now he could have obtained a winning attack with:} 17. hxg6 fxg6 18. g5
Nh5 19. Rxh5 $1 gxh5 20. Bh3 $18) 13. O-O-O {[#] White's kingside attack is
quite serious and Black has to play precisely to neutralize it:} a6 ({Once
again, central counterplay:} 13... d5 {does not work well.} 14. cxd5 exd5 15.
exd5 ({Quick attack with} 15. h4 $1 {is even stronger.} dxe4 16. h5 Rc8 17. Kb1
$40) 15... Rc8 16. Nc6 Bxc6 17. dxc6 Rxc6 18. Bb5 $16 {1-0 (35) Jones,G (2675)
-Antonio,V (2435) Sharjah UAE 2018}) 14. h4 Nh5 $1 15. Rh3 Qf6 {[#] This looks
like the most reliable defence for Black. Still, his position is slightly
inferior due to all these dark-squared weaknesses.} 16. Nde2 Qe7 17. g4 Ng7 18.
Qd2 Ne5 19. Nf4 Rfd8 20. Kb1 $14 {Grandelius-Chigaev, Porto Carras 2018}) ({
I mentioned earlier than f2-f3 creates weaknesses on the dark-squares complex
and} 10... Nh5 {is an attempt to take advantage of that. However, White can
continue with his program nevertheless:} 11. h4 $1 {[#]} e6 {Somehow, these
central break attempts seldom seem to work for Black in these positions.}
({It was clearly better to complete the initial idea:} 11... Ng3 12. Rh3 Nxf1
13. Kxf1 {when Black is missing his knight in defence but can use its absence
to open the f-file for counterplay.} Qc8 (13... h5 14. Bh6 $16) 14. b3 Nc6 15.
Nxc6 Bxc6 16. h5 f5 {Black is not getting checkmated after this move,
though White enjoys a positional advantage due to a better pawn structure.} 17.
exf5 Qxf5 18. hxg6 Qxg6 19. Re1 $14) 12. Rh3 $1 $16 d5 13. cxd5 exd5 14. g4 Nf6
15. e5 Nfd7 16. f4 Nc5 17. O-O-O Qc8 18. Kb1 Qxg4 19. h5 $18 {and White won in
a crushing attack in Grandelius-Hagen, A, Helsingor 2018}) 11. O-O-O {[#] How
is Black to organize counterplay in this position? There are two possible
approaches. He can either attack the exposed c-pawn with ...Nc6-e5 and ...Rc8/
Qc7, or prepare the opening of the queenside with ...a6-b5, even at a cost of a
pawn. In practice, both approaches have been tried.} Ne5 ({In two games in
which Black tried the second approach, things did not work out well for them:} 
11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 a6 13. Kb1 Bc6 14. g4 Rb8 15. h4 b5 16. h5 $40 {[#]
White's kingside assault is quicker - he is about to open the h-file and trade
the main defender of black king with g4-g5. Meanwhile, Black does not have any
threats to speak of.} e6 17. hxg6 fxg6 18. g5 b4 {and here in the game
Grandelius,N (2647)-Kotronias,V (2524) London ENG 2017 ½-½ (33)} {White
would have pretty much won on the spot if he had included another piece in the
attack:} 19. Bh3 $1 $18 {though he got a winning position in the game, too.}) (
{and also:} 11... Qb8 12. Kb1 Rc8 {This plan strikes me as being too slow.} 13.
Nxc6 Bxc6 14. h4 a6 15. Bh6 Bh8 16. h5 $40 b5 17. hxg6 fxg6 {and now in the
game Paravyan-Belyakov, Moscow 2018, White should have continued} 18. g3 $1 {
followed by 19.Bh3, creating some nasty mating threats before Black has even
managed to open any attacking files on the other side of the board. Another
common theme in this variation is that somehow even strong White players keep
missing Bf1-h3-e6 attacking idea!}) 12. Bh6 {I think that White should
immediately take advantage of the fact that Black had released the tension on
d4 with his last move, and trade the dark-squared bishops.} ({In another game
in this line, White played more reservedly:} 12. Kb1 Rc8 13. b3 a6 14. Be2 e6 {
giving Black plenty of time to complete his development and prepare ...b7-b5
and ...d6-d5 breaks. Besides, with black dark-squared bishop still on the
board, the weaknesses around white king incurred by the move b2-b3 are felt
more strongly.} 15. g4 {[#]} ({In the light of Black's active possibility on
move 15, it may have been more circumspect to do some prophylaxis with} 15. Rc1
$5) {and now Black had an opportunity to stir complications with:} 15... d5 $1
({In the game, Black missed this opportunity to sharpen the game.} 15... Qc7
16. Rc1 Rfd8 17. Rhd1 $14 {White can claim a slight edge here, though it is
still anyone's game, of course. However, Black quickly self-destructed with an
incorrect piece sacrifice.} Qe7 18. h4 Nexg4 $2 19. fxg4 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 Bxe4+
21. Bd3 Qb7 22. Qc2 $18 {1-0 (22) Paravyan,D-Triapishko,A Loo 2018}) 16. cxd5
exd5 17. g5 Nxe4 $1 18. fxe4 dxe4 $44 {with an obvious compensation for the
sacrificed piece.}) 12... Rc8 ({The alternative way to attack the pawn} 12...
Qc7 {is hardly an improvement for Black in the view of the pawn sacrifice:} 13.
h4 $1 ({I also see nothing wrong with} 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. b3 {as in the main
line. The king goes to b2 and White should have everything under control.})
13... Nxc4 14. Bxc4 Qxc4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. h5 Kh8 17. g4 Rg8 {Black averted
the mating attack, but after} 18. Kb1 $1 $36 {he is reminded that danger can
come from the other flank, as well. White is threatening Rc1 when black queen
lacks a safe spot.}) {Here, I would suggest a new idea:} 13. Bxg7 $146 ({
Instead of the sharper} 13. h4 $5 Nxc4 14. Bxc4 Rxc4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. h5 {
when White seemed to have a strong attack, but Black could have obtained
counterplay in the centre with} e5 $1 ({Instead,} 16... Qc8 {was played in a
rapid game between two strong GMs. Due to shorter time control, the game was
full of mistakes and turnarounds, so it stops being theoretically interesting
around move 18 when White had a nice position.} 17. Kb1 a6 18. g4 $40 {
1-0 (50) Lupulescu,C (2649)-Kovalev,V (2649) Riga LAT 2019}) 17. Ndb5 d5 $1 18.
exd5 a6 $132) 13... Kxg7 14. b3 {[#] If we compare this to 12.Kb1 line, we can
notice an important difference - white king feels safer once the dark-squared
bishops have been traded. It can be 'fianchettoed' on b2, just like its
colleague on the other flank. However, the fundamental difference is that
White has a simple plan to expand on the kingside with g2-g4(-g5), h3-h4-h5,
etc., while Black does not have such possibilities as his pawn breaks ...b6-b5
and ...d6-d5 are well defended. With more space and a safer king, I think that
White should be more than happy to go for this position.} a6 15. Kb2 $16 *

