{[%evp 0,47,22,28,21,-14,35,37,37,33,42,42,36,27,32,10,21,14,17,20,30,31,41,27,
35,46,48,57,49,51,46,20,42,55,58,52,72,75,87,79,76,74,90,68,68,68,78,81,75,75]
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be3 c5 7. Nf3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Nc6 9. Be2 {[#] We have reached one of the main lines of the Maroczy bind
by transposition. The move h2-h3 is rarely played in this structure because
White usually defends the e4-pawn with a non-complementary f2-f3. However, in
this variation White intends to defend the e4-pawn with a piece rather than
the f-pawn, so h3 becomes a useful move that takes control over the g4-square.}
Bd7 ({Another move order to get the position from the main line is:} 9... Nxd4
10. Bxd4 Bd7 ({Additional option for Black is} 10... Qa5 11. O-O Be6 {but this
plan does not work that well in this particular variation:} 12. f4 Rfc8 13. b3
a6 {Vishnu,P (2538)-Kaasen,T (2399) Riga 2017 1-0 (33)} 14. a4 $1 $16) 11. O-O
Bc6 12. Qc2) ({Creative Latvian GM Kovalenko tried} 9... Qb6 {but his opening
experiment quickly backfired after:} 10. Nb3 Qc7 11. O-O b6 12. Nd5 Qb7 13. Qc2
Nd7 14. f4 $1 Nc5 15. f5 $16 {Lupulescu-Kovalenko, Skopje 2019}) 10. O-O Nxd4 (
{Some strong players have tried to prepare ...b7-b5 break with} 10... a6 {
[#] but White can avoid the exchange of knights with} 11. Nf3 $1 Rc8 ({More to
the point is} 11... Rb8 {when, among several good options, White may even
allow Black to execute his idea, and play:} 12. a3 $5 b5 13. cxb5 axb5 14. b4
$14 {when b5-pawn may also prove to be a weakness.}) 12. Rc1 Qa5 13. a3 Be6 14.
Nd5 Nd7 15. Bd2 Qd8 16. b4 $16 {1-0 (53) Grandelius,N (2665)-Sviridov,V (2504)
Minsk 2017}) 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. Qc2 {[#] This is White's key idea in this
variation. The queen assumes a solid position on c2, vacating d1-square for
the rook and threatening to break in the centre with e4-e5 or c4-c5.} a5 ({
There is a reason why Black usually makes this preparatory move - in case of
the immediate} 12... Nd7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 {White takes up even more space with}
14. b4 $1 $14 {[#] and Black is quite cramped.} Nf6 15. Rad1 ({Besides the
text move, White has many good options; for example:} 15. Qd3 $5 $146 Bd7 16.
a3 Be6 17. Nd5 $14) 15... Qb6 16. a3 Rfd8 17. Kh1 $14 {preparing pawn
expansion on the kingside in the game Cornette, M (2590)-Van Foreest, J (2519)
Vaujany 2015 ½-½ (59)}) ({A waiting tactic with something like} 12... Qc7 {
is also possible, though Black's position is quite passive. For example:} 13.
Bd3 (13. Rad1 $5 b5 14. cxb5 Bxe4 15. Qb3 $14) 13... Rac8 14. Qd2 e6 15. Rac1
Rfe8 16. Rfe1 Qb8 17. b4 $14 {1-0 (50) Kuljasevic,D (2546)-Omar,N (2354) Biel
2017}) 13. Rad1 {[#]} Nd7 {This is the main move, but considering the problems
that Black have after this, the alternative 13...a4 seems more promising.} ({
If I were Black, I would rather go for} 13... a4 $5 {which is a typical move
in the Maroczy bind that provides a safe and active square for the black queen,
while also putting some pressure on white queenside pawns.} 14. c5 Qa5 15. cxd6
exd6 {[#] Black made a concession in the form of a backward isolated pawn on
d6, but he is not facing any tactical problems with his queen on the d-file 
and may hope to get counterplay thanks to his active pieces. White should
 play precisely to maintain his positional edge here.} 16. a3 {
I prefer this move that fixes the queenside structure} ({over} 16. Bf3 {
when Black may obtain some practical counterplay with} a3 17. Qb3 axb2 18. Qxb2
Qa3 19. Qa1 Ne8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (24) Dragnev,V (2466)-Piorun,K (2640) Germany 2018
}) 16... Rfe8 {and now, White can improve over the game Pantzar-Lahav,
Stockholm 2019 by defending the vulnerable e-pawn with} 17. f3 $5 $146 {
[#] Granted, this move creates some weaknesses on the dark squares, but Black
can not take advantage of them, as can be seen from the critical
variations below. This way, the e4-pawn is defended more soundly and other
white pieces have more freedom; for example, White can bring his bishop to an
active c4-square instead of the passive f3, his queen can now move to d2/f2,
etc. The backward d6-pawn is, of course, the main long-term target.} d5 (17...
Nh5 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Rf2 Nf4 20. Bf1 Qg5 21. Kh2 $14) 18. e5 Nh5 19. f4 Ng3
20. Rfe1 Nf5 21. Bf2 d4 22. Ne4 $14) (13... Qc7 {is also not ideal, as it
allows White to play} 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. exd5 $14 {[#] with a favorable pawn
structure transformation.} Nd7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qc3+ Kg8 18. Rd4 Nc5 19. Rfd1
a4 20. h4 $1 $40 {Rakhmanov-Skoberne, Batumi 2018}) 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Bg4 $1
$36 {[#] This move was first played by GM David Anton Guijarro in 2014 and it
has scored a fantastic 86% for White in just over 50 games in the database.
Black's problem is that he does not have a good way to evacuate his queen from
d8 in the view of c4-c5 and e4-e5 breaks.} Ne5 {or 15...Nf6 usually lead to
the same position after move 17.} ({The other knight move} 15... Nc5 {is met
by the alternative pawn break:} 16. e5 $1 f5 17. Be2 f4 18. Nd5 $1 dxe5 19. Qc3
$36 {Mista-Galperin, Krakow 2017}) (15... a4 {is too slow now, due to} 16. Rfe1
$1 Qa5 17. Bxd7 Bxd7 18. e5 $16) 16. c5 $1 {Now we can see why h2-h3 is an
integral part of this setup - the bishop is defended on g4.} b5 $5 {This is
the most recent attempt by Black in this line. Currently, youngest GM in the
world, Indian Gukesh, D, played this just a couple of months ago. It will not
change the evaluation of the position as clearly better for White, but playing
actively on the queenside to compensate for the weak d6-pawn makes a lot of
sense - similar to 14...a4!? line.} ({The most common Black's reply is} 16...
Nxg4 17. hxg4 Qc8 {[#] but White obtains a great position after} 18. cxd6 Qxg4
({or} 18... exd6 19. f3 Qe6 20. Rd4 $16 {and simply tripling against the
backward d6-pawn was decisive in the game Perunovic, M (2597)-Cirovic, M (2226)
Podgorica MNE 2019 1-0 (42)}) 19. dxe7 Rfe8 20. Nd5 $1 Bxd5 21. Qc3+ Kg8 22.
exd5 Rxe7 23. d6 Rd7 24. Rd5 $16 {This position was reached in a high-profile
game Cheparinov, I-Amin, B Zagreb 2018. White had a classical advantage of the
advanced passed pawn in the centre, which he eventually converted to a full
point.}) 17. cxd6 exd6 {[#] At this point, it is likely that White's play
could be improved with} 18. Nd5 $5 $146 ({In the original game, White played} 
18. b3 {but this move does not look essential to me as it weakens the support
of c3-knight. Black could have continued} Nxg4 ({He did not have enough
compensation after the game move} 18... Qb6 19. Rxd6 Qc5 20. Rd2 b4 21. Nd5
Qxc2 22. Rxc2 $16 {1-0 (42) Donchenko,A (2615)-Gukesh,D (2520) Biel SUI 2019})
19. hxg4 Rc8 {and White probably has to play Nc3-d5 anyway, so why not do it
on move 18?}) 18... Re8 19. Be2 Rc8 20. Qb3 $14 {with a pleasant edge for
White.} *

