{[%evp 0,41,27,32,22,-4,34,33,32,45,46,44,39,14,36,21,20,30,25,22,40,34,34,39,
65,62,62,47,55,38,55,56,55,40,61,46,63,54,59,59,80,85,64,75]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be3 c5 7. Nf3 {[#]} Qa5 {This is the main
alternative to 7...cxd4. Black tries to cause inconvenience to White's
development by pinning the c3-knight.} ({An interesting sideline is} 7... Na6 {
when White can continue keeping the tension in the centre with} 8. Be2 ({
or block it with} 8. d5 e6 9. Bd3 exd5 10. exd5 {transposing into the position
from Chapter 7.}) 8... cxd4 (8... b6 {is too passive, allowing White to get a
favourable version of Benoni with} 9. d5 e6 10. O-O exd5 11. exd5 $14 {[#]
White enjoys extra space and long-term prospects of exploiting the Achilles
heel of black position - d6-pawn.} Re8 12. Bd3 Nc7 13. a4 a6 14. Qd2 Bb7 15. b3
$14 {Yilmaz-Selbes, Izmir 2016}) 9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. Qc2 b6 {[#] It is more common
for Black to enter this type of position via 7...exd4 and 8...b6, keeping
the flexibility of his queen's knight, as we have seen in Chapter 4. From d7, it
can go to either e5 and c5, or even just remain on d7. Here, it is committed
to c5-square from where it puts pressure on the e4-pawn. However, it is not
clear what its role is once White defends his central pawn. It may even
obstruct Black's typical play on the c-file or run into b2-b4 tempo in certain
lines. White has several good options here. The most enterprising approach is}
11. O-O-O $5 {leading to sharp play similar to the main line in Chapter 4.} ({
A less risky course of action is} 11. O-O Bb7 12. Bf3 $1 {[#] This move
contains more venom than it may seem at first. Besides defending the pawn on
e4 (White can later play g2-g3 and Bf3-g2 if he finds placement of the bishop
on f3 awkward), White also creates a tactical threat of e4-e5 after he removes
the knight from c5 with b2-b4.} Rc8 {This is a bold move since it leaves the
b7-bishop undefended and allows the aforementioned tactical shot. Black could
play something like 12...Rb8 or 12...Qc7 instead, but then he could hardly
complete the ideal regrouping as in the game Cramling-Gukesh below.} 13. b4 $1
$146 {This direct move is an improvement} ({over} 13. Rad1 {which was rather
meek and posed Black no problems to achieve his ideal setup in this variation:}
Qc7 14. b3 Qb8 15. Qb1 Rfe8 16. Rfe1 a6 17. a4 e6 18. Nde2 Bc6 19. Bf4 Red8 $11
{1/2-1/2 (23) Cramling, P (2454)-Gukesh, D (2533) Brest FRA 2019}) {According to
my analysis, Black loses material with little to no compensation or is simply
positionally worse after any of his three possible responses:} 13... Na6 (13...
Ncd7 14. e5 $1 dxe5 15. Bxb7 exd4 16. Bxc8 dxe3 17. Bxd7 exf2+ 18. Rxf2 Qxd7
19. Rd1 $14) (13... Ncxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 d5 16. Bf3 e5 17. Nb3 $16) 14.
Qb3 Qc7 15. Rac1 $1 Qxc4 16. e5 Qxb3 17. axb3 dxe5 (17... Bxf3 18. exf6 Bxf6
19. gxf3 Nxb4 20. Rfd1 $16) 18. Bxb7 Rxc3 19. Rxc3 exd4 20. Bxd4 Nxb4 21. Rd1
$14) ({Another reasonable option is} 11. b4 Ne6 (11... Ncd7 12. O-O Bb7 13.
Rac1 Rc8 14. Qb1 a6 15. Rfd1 $14) {when White also has an early improvement in}
12. Rd1 $146 (12. Nb3 a5 13. bxa5 bxa5 14. a4 Nd7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (47) Granda
Zuniga,J (2685)-Maze,S (2582) Sitges ESP 2015}) 12... Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Be6 14. O-O
$14 {which is similar to one of the positions from Chapter 5 when Black does not
play ...a7-a5 in time.}) 11... Bb7 12. f3 Nh5 {[#] This is an attempt to slow
down White's typical pawn storm on the kingside. Here, too, I can suggest an
early improvement:} 13. h4 $5 $146 {using an idea from a game of GM Grandelius
(from Chapter 4).} ({In the game Iturrizaga-Gukesh, Ho Chi Minh City 2019, the
GM playing White continued} 13. g4 Ng3 14. Rhg1 Nxe2+ 15. Qxe2 Rc8 ({but Black
could have obtained counterplay with:} 15... a6 16. Kb1 b5 $1 17. Nf5 Bxc3 $1
18. Bxc5 Be5 $13) 16. h4 Ba6 17. Kb1 Na4 18. Ncb5 $14 {with an advantage that
he later converted.}) 13... Ng3 14. Rh3 Nxe2+ 15. Qxe2 h5 {Otherwise White
pushes h4-h5 himself.} 16. Kb1 Qd7 17. Rhh1 $36 {and White just wants to
attack 'caveman style' with g2-g4, hxg4, h4-h5, Qe2-h2 etc.}) 8. Bd3 {This is
the best way to defend the e4-pawn.} (8. Nd2 $6 cxd4 9. Nb3 {[#] was answered
brilliantly in the game Firouzja-Karthikeyan, M, Xingtai 2019:} Qxc3+ $3 10.
bxc3 dxe3 $44 11. f3 Nh5 12. Qc1 Bh6 13. g4 Nf4 $36 {and this unusual position
was easier to play with Black, who won at the end.}) 8... Nfd7 {
Black switches to attacking the other central pawn.} (8... Nc6 {is premature
in the view of} 9. d5 Nb4 10. Bb1 ({White can even play} 10. Be2 $5 $146 {
since Black's only attempt to justify his previous play} Nxe4 {does not seem
to be sufficient after:} 11. Nxe4 Nc2+ 12. Kf1 Nxa1 13. Qxa1 b5 14. Bd2 $16)
10... b5 11. cxb5 e6 12. dxe6 ({White also passed up on another strong
tactical option:} 12. O-O exd5 13. e5 $1 dxe5 14. Bxc5 $16 d4 15. Qa4 $1) 12...
Bxe6 13. O-O Rfd8 14. Qc1 a6 15. bxa6 Qxa6 16. Bh6 $16 {and Black had no
compensation for the sacrificed pawn in Esipenko, A (2621)-Injac, T (2305) Konya
TUR 2019 1-0 (34)}) ({Black did not get too far with} 8... e5 {either:} 9. d5
Nh5 10. Nd2 Qd8 11. g3 $16 {in one of the early grandmaster games in this
system: Bondarevsky-Barden, Hastings 1960}) (8... cxd4 {usually just
transposes to the main line after} 9. Nxd4 Nc6 10. O-O Nd7 ({though an
additional option is} 10... Bd7 {However, this runs into:} 11. Nb3 Qd8 12. c5
$1 Be6 13. cxd6 exd6 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 $14 {[#] with a position similar to
13...a4 line Chapter 5.} Qa5 16. Qf3 Nd7 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Qg3 Ne5 19. Be2 Qb6
20. Rad1 Rac8 21. Rd2 $16 {1-0 (65) Antonsen,M (2445)-Berg,E (2551) Sweden 2018
})) 9. Be2 $1 {Playing with the bishop for the second time in a row, but this
is the most precise move.} ({The point is that in case of} 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be2 {
Black can take control over the d4-square with} e5 $1 11. dxc5 dxc5 12. Nd5 Re8
13. a3 Qd8 14. b4 b6 15. Rb1 Nd4 $13 {Parligras-Tzidkiya, Netanya 2019}) 9...
cxd4 ({Now,} 9... Nc6 {is simply met by} 10. d5 {and the knight does not have
good squares.}) 10. Nxd4 Nc6 11. O-O {[#] As a result of the opening, we have
some version of the Maroczy bind middlegame on the board. I don't quite see
how winning a tempo to play Qa5 and Nd7 helps Black's chances. In theory, he
should be happy to trade a couple of pieces in a position in which his
opponent holds the space advantage, but he still lacks serious counterplay. 
In practice, White has done well, as can be seen from several games below:}
Nxd4 ({Other options are:} 11... Nc5 12. Nb3 (12. Rb1 $5) 12... Nxb3 13. axb3
Qd8 14. Qd2 $14 {Cvitan-Brodsky, Katowice 1992}) ({and:} 11... Qd8 12. Qd2 Nc5
13. Rad1 Bd7 14. f4 Na4 15. Nxa4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 17. Qxd4 Bxa4 18. b3 Bc6
19. e5 dxe5 20. Qxe5 $14 {Thybo-Kotronias, Aarhus 2019}) 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4
Qc5 (13... Ne5 14. Rad1 Be6 15. b3 a6 16. Qe3 b5 17. f4 b4 {0-1 (30) Pechac,J 
(2469)-Mazur, S (2440) Ruzomberok SVK 2019} 18. Nd5 $16) 14. Qd2 {Some strong
players have traded queens here, counting on a small plus in the endgame.
However, I would prefer keeping queens on the board because Black may not find
good employment for his queen in this structure, while White may use his queen
for an attack against the slightly weakened black kingside.} Nf6 (14... Ne5 $6 {
allowed} 15. Nd5 {and Black was quickly busted:} Re8 16. b4 Qc6 17. f4 Nd7 18.
Qd4 b6 19. f5 $40 {1-0 (27) Reuker,J (2404)-Syrov,A (2295) Dresden GER 2018}) {
White has a pleasant choice here. I like the following simple approach:} 15.
Nd5 $1 ({although there is also nothing wrong with a more methodical approach,
such as in the following game:} 15. Rfe1 Be6 16. b3 Rfc8 17. Rac1 a6 18. Bf3
Rc7 19. Na4 Qe5 20. Nb6 Re8 21. Nd5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (105) Rodshtein,M (2695)
-Pichot,A (2565) Douglas 2017}) 15... Nxd5 16. exd5 $14 {[#] Despite trading
another pair of pieces, Black is far from solving his problems. By taking back
on d5 with the e-pawn, White has opened the e-file, exposing the backward
e7-pawn as a target in the new pawn structure.} e5 {It makes sense to play
this move to avoid positional torture, but Black is going to be saddled with
another pawn weakness - on d6. In the game, she did not manage to compensate
for that weakness and she soon lost the pawn.} 17. dxe6 Bxe6 18. Rac1 Rac8 19.
Rfd1 Rfd8 20. b3 Qe5 21. Rc3 $16 {preparing to complete the siege of the lone
pawn with Rc3-d3 in Cornette, M-L'Ami, A Reykjavik 2019} *

