{[%evp 0,77,22,27,29,-9,41,36,33,37,33,33,17,20,35,38,62,62,52,48,59,72,83,11,
11,25,25,27,13,40,48,42,43,43,35,30,54,53,52,49,69,54,86,67,71,72,63,86,76,48,
191,162,98,73,136,129,190,201,197,179,161,185,171,195,195,186,172,201,200,200,
215,275,306,229,343,340,418,422,425,454]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4
d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be3 c5 7. d5 {[#] This is an alternative to 7.Nf3. It is
mostly a matter of preference for White players. Those who enjoy having a
stable center with extra space will probably prefer 7.d5 over 7.Nf3. As usual
in such positions, Black has two ways to attack and undermine white pawn
center:} {Most players go for the Benoni approach with} e6 ({This is probably
for a good reason since the Benko gambit approach} 7... b5 8. cxb5 a6 {fails
to impress after:} 9. a4 Qa5 10. Bd2 $1 {[#] White does not mind spending a
tempo with the bishop to neutralize Black's tactical attempts.} axb5 (10... Qb4
{is principled, but also risky business for Black. His queen may get caught on
enemy's territory. The following games prove that White has a large advantage
in this line.} 11. Bd3 Nfd7 (11... c4 12. Bc2 Nfd7 13. Nge2 $5 {This is an
extra option for White after early 11...c4.} Nc5 14. O-O Nb3 15. Bxb3 cxb3 {
1-0 (58) Varga,P (2478)-Sikanjic,B (2113) Rijeka 2003} 16. Be3 $5 $146 Nd7 17.
Nd4 $18) 12. Nf3 c4 13. Bc2 Qxb2 (13... Nc5 14. O-O Nb3 15. Bxb3 cxb3 {1-0 (42)
Marin,M (2520)-Ardeleanu,A (2370) Bucharest 1994} 16. Ra3 $146 axb5 17. Rxb3
Qc4 18. axb5 $18) 14. Rb1 Qa3 15. Ne2 Nc5 16. O-O c3 17. Be3 axb5 18. axb5 f5
19. exf5 Bxf5 20. Nfd4 $18 {1-0 (42) Kozul,Z (2602)-Pancevski,F (2470) Plovdiv
2012}) 11. Bxb5 Ba6 (11... Qb4 12. Bd3 c4 13. Bc2 Ba6 14. Rb1 Nbd7 15. Nge2 Qb6
16. O-O $16 {1-0 (47) Kazhgaleyev,M (2596)-Shirazi,K (2426) Issy les
Moulineaux 2004}) 12. Ra3 $1 Nbd7 ({preparing to answer} 12... Qb4 {with} 13.
Rb3) 13. Nf3 Bxb5 14. Nxb5 Qb6 15. Qc2 $16 {with an ideal anti-Benko setup for
White in Salgado Lopez-Fedoseev, Plovdiv 2012}) 8. Bd3 {It is important to
play this move as soon as possible in order to take away ...Bc8-f5 option from
Black after the exchange of pawns on d5.} (8. Nf3 {is less accurate due to}
exd5 9. exd5 Bf5) 8... exd5 {This is, of course, the main continuation,} ({
although there is something to be said for a rare, reasonable waiting
approach} 8... Na6 $5 {[#] Black keeps flexibility in the centre and flirts
with blocking of the position in case White plays a2-a4. If White does not
take measures to prevent ...b7-b5, then Black plans to take on d5 and play on
the queenside. I think that this is a very reasonable practical concept
because White's best moves are not obvious.} 9. Nf3 Re8 ({Black can also play} 
9... Nc7 {immediately. There is not much difference compared to the main line;
White can either prevent ...b7-b5 with a slightly weakening} 10. a4 ({or keep
his pawn structure intact with slightly awkward} 10. Qb3 $5 $146 {The only
difference compared to 9...Re8 is that Black can save that tempo and initiate
complications immediately:} exd5 11. exd5 b5 ({or} 11... Rb8 12. O-O b5 13.
cxb5 Nxb5 14. Bxb5 a6 15. a4 $14) 12. cxb5 Bb7 13. Bc4 Nd7 14. O-O Nb6 15. a4
$14 {but I don't see that he is getting enough for the pawn either way.}) 10...
Na6 11. O-O e5 {This position has been seen in two black games by GM
Chatalbashev. Despite the slight structural weakening on the queenside, White
should keep a slight edge thanks to space advantage and perfectly placed minor
pieces. For example:} 12. Bg5 $5 $146 Nb4 13. Bb1 h6 14. Bd2 Nh5 15. Ra3 Nf4
16. Ne2 $14) 10. O-O Nc7 11. a4 {GM Adhiban notes: "Not finding a satisfactory
way to defend against ...b5 and at the same time be ready for e5, I decided to
allow Na6-b4."} ({However, there might be a way to get the best of both
worlds:} 11. Qb3 $5 $146 {[#] White can stop ...b7-b5 with this move without
weakening the b4-square. True, the queen looks misplaced on b3, but as we know,
pieces can move back and pawns cannot! Black should probably try to keep the
tension with some useful-looking moves, such as} b6 ({since direct attempts to
define the pawn structure seem to be in White's favour:} 11... exd5 12. exd5 b5
13. cxb5 Bb7 14. Bc4 Nd7 15. Bg5 $1 $16) ({and:} 11... e5 12. Qc2 Nh5 13. Rfe1
Nf4 14. Bf1 f5 15. a3 $14) 12. Rfe1 Rb8 13. Rad1 $14 {and it is a waiting game
in which it is not easy to tell who will win, but I think that White should be
able to eventually prove a plus.}) 11... Na6 {From here on, I provide some
notes by GM Adhiban.} 12. Nd2 ({More human would be} 12. Rc1 $5 Nb4 13. Bb1 b6
14. Qd2 {looks quite nice for White.}) 12... Nb4 13. Be2 (13. Bb1 $5 {I wasn't
sure if the bishop would have a useful role, but possibly this was better than
the game continuation.}) 13... b6 $1 {Aimed against e5. Here I started to feel
a bit unpleasant as I wasn't sure which plan to embark on!} 14. Qb3 $5 {
Following the oldest saying, "When you don't know what to do connect your
rooks!"} a6 15. Rae1 {Now that they hsvr been connected, it was time for phase
2: Activate the rooks!} Ra7 $1 {Pono is not lagging behind and follows the
same idea!} 16. Qd1 $1 {Job done!} Rae7 17. Qb1 $1 {Now I have prevented any
possible exchange on e4 (like in Karjakin-Caruana 2014) and also restrict the
strong knight on b4.} Qc7 18. Bf4 $5 {Slowly improving my piece positions and
also fighting against the centre control and preventing ...exd5 which will be
met by cxd5 followed by Nc4.} e5 {I surprised to see that he was the one who
made the ultimate decision to close the position.} 19. Be3 $13 {1/2-1/2 (35)
Adhiban,B (2671)-Ponomariov,R (2686) Linares 2018 CBM 186 [Adhiban,B]}) 9. exd5
{[#] White should go for this version of the Benoni since the bishop is not
placed well on e3 in case of 9.cxd5. Still, this is fine for White because he
can usually count on a small positional advantage in this structure due to
more space and a potentially weak d6-pawn.} Na6 {This is the most direct
attempt to take advantage of White's development scheme.} ({The most serious
alternative is} 9... Re8 {after which White can play} 10. Nf3 {transposing
into an important variation of the Benoni with exd5. Black has interesting
options, such as} Bh6 ({and} 10... Rxe3+ $5 11. fxe3 Qe7) 11. O-O Bxe3 12. fxe3
{and a few more.  Since this variation has been thoroughly analyzed by GM
Mihail Marin in 'Play the Makogonov against KID' database (also published by
Modern chess), I would like to refer you to his analysis.}) ({Black has
several other alternatives. Some players have tried to force the issue with
bishop's development with} 9... Bf5 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. Qc2 $14 {[#] but I think
that Black does not get enough in return for such structural damage.} Ne4 12.
Nxe4 fxe4 13. Qxe4 f5 14. Qc2 Na6 15. Ne2 $16 {and Black had no compensation
for the pawn in Postny-Costachi, Graz 2017}) ({Another common idea for Black
in such positions is to play ...f7-f5 and thus} 9... Nfd7 {is also an option.
After:} 10. Nf3 f5 11. Qd2 Ne5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 {in the game Cuenca
Jimenez-Wieczorek, Roquetas de Mar 2018, White could have obtained good
attacking chances on the kingside with} 13. Bh6 $146 Rf7 14. O-O-O $36 {
preparing to open the h-file with h3-h4-h5.}) ({The following game is a good
example of what happens if Black plays inaccurately in this structure:} 9... a6
10. a4 Re8 11. Nf3 Nh5 12. O-O Nd7 13. Qd2 Ne5 14. Be2 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Ng3 16.
Rfe1 Nf5 17. Bg5 Rxe1+ 18. Rxe1 f6 {This is a sad necessity.} 19. Bf4 Nd4 20.
Bd1 $16 {1-0 (48) Tikkanen,H (2544)-Berg,E (2539) Lidkoping 2013}) 10. Nf3 Nb4
{This aggressive sortie looks like the critical attempt for Black.} ({A more
positional alternative is} 10... Nc7 11. a4 ({In one of the early games in the
Makogonov variation, Black obtained good counterplay after} 11. O-O b5 $132 {
Bondarevsky-Petrosian,T, Moscow 1951}) 11... Na6 {which is a typical
back-and-forth knight manoeuvre in the Benoni.} ({Game Sargissian, G (2668)-Can,
E (2555) Jerusalem 2015 ½-½ (32) saw Black employ the same plan as in 9...
Nfd7 line:} 11... Nd7 12. O-O Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Qd2 f5 {and now, similar
to that line, I think that White should use a different concept and keep more
tension in the position with:} 15. Bg5 $5 $146 Qe8 16. Rfe1 Qf7 17. Bf1 Re8 18.
g3 Bd7 19. h4 $14) {Despite Black taking control of the b4-square, White still
keeps an edge with} 12. Rc1 Nb4 13. Bb1 {still keeping the c8-bishop out of
the game.} a6 {[#] Here, White needs to be precise with} 14. Qd2 $146 ({
instead,} 14. O-O {allows} b5 $1 15. axb5 axb5 16. Nxb5 Ba6 $44 {with active
play for Black in the game Ermenkov-Pavlidis, A, Chalkidiki 2008, based on the
following little tactic:} 17. Na3 Nfxd5 $1 18. cxd5 Bxf1 19. Qxf1 Bxb2 20. Nc4
Bxc1 21. Bxc1 $13) 14... Bd7 15. O-O b5 16. b3 bxc4 17. bxc4 $14 {and White is
slightly better in this fairly static position. The knight stands nicely on
b4-outpost, but is is not nearly as effective as it seems. Meanwhile, White
will focus on the kingside, where he has an advantage in space and forces.})
11. Be2 {A necessary retreat.} (11. Bb1 $6 {is surprisingly strongly met by} b5
$1 12. Nxb5 Ba6 $36 {and White is facing problems.}) 11... Bf5 12. Rc1 Ne4 $6 {
Once again, this is the most forcing continuation, but objectively it is
suspicious because of White's next move.} ({It is safer to play} 12... Re8 13.
a3 Na6 {as in the game Dimitrov,V (2309)-Damljanovic,B (2468) Veliko Gradiste
SRB 2019 0-1 (22). Black has lost some time with his knight, but so did White
with his light-squared bishop. However, Black managed to develop his bishop to
f5, which is a small achievement. Nevertheless, I believe that White should
obtain a small edge with} 14. Bd3 $146 Ne4 (14... Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Qd7 16. O-O $14
{leaves Black quite cramped, while White can expand on both sides of the board.
}) 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. O-O $1 {White ignores the light-squared bishop and
continues to pursue his usual plans.} Bf5 17. Qd2 $14) 13. g4 $1 {[#] This is
the point. We enter tactical complications that eventually favour White.} Nxc3
14. bxc3 Nxa2 15. gxf5 Nxc1 16. Qxc1 {Amin Bassem already had this position
this year, only with black pieces against Cuenca Jimenez in a game that he
barely drew. A few months later he decided to use it against Fedorov with
White!} Qf6 $6 {The endgame is quite cheerless for Black.} ({White would be
put under a more serious test with} 16... a5 $5 17. Kd2 a4 18. Qc2 a3 19. Ra1
$16) 17. fxg6 Qxc3+ 18. Qxc3 Bxc3+ 19. Kd1 hxg6 20. Kc2 Bg7 21. Rb1 b6 22. h4
$1 Rfe8 23. Bd3 Kf8 24. h5 a5 25. h6 Bf6 26. Kb3 a4+ 27. Ka3 $18 Bc3 28. Rxb6
Reb8 29. Rb5 Bb4+ 30. Ka2 Ke7 31. Bf4 Bc3 32. Ng5 f5 33. Ne6 Rxb5 34. cxb5 a3
35. Nxc5 Bd4 36. Bg5+ Kf7 37. Nb7 Bxf2 38. Nxd6+ Kg8 39. Nc4 {1-0 (39) Amin,
B-Fedorov, A France tt 2019} *

