{[%evp 0,49,14,20,20,-12,38,37,37,37,37,46,32,21,57,5,36,45,49,60,63,34,76,82,
62,49,67,70,43,36,34,55,34,28,43,40,67,27,55,66,99,93,93,61,31,2,1,-3,0,-24,0,
-24]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be3 Na6 {[#] This is
perhaps the most flexible move that Black has at his disposal. a6 is usually a
good square for the knight in most structures in this variation, so Black just
develops and does not show his cards in the center just yet. White's most
principled response is} 7. g4 {because he does not want to commit his king's
knight to f3 so early.} ({Of course, it is possible to play} 7. Nf3 {but just
as on move 6, it would allow} e5 8. d5 Nh5 $5 {as explained in the
Introduction. 7.g4 eliminates this option for Black.}) 7... c6 $5 {Once again,
this is the most flexible option for Black. His two main ideas are ...e7-e5
and ...Na6-c7, followed by the flank break ...b7-b5.} ({Now} 7... e5 8. d5 {
transposes into Chapter 3.}) ({Another option is} 7... c5 {when White should
treat this as an extended fianchetto variation, rather than the Benoni and play
} 8. Nge2 {[#] Black have tried two approaches in this position. The first one
is} b6 ({and the second one releases central tension:} 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nc5
10. Bg2 $14 {[#] My experience with the fianchetto variation of the KID tells
me that White should have a solid edge in this type of the position and the
following games confirm it:} a6 (10... b6 11. O-O Bb7 12. Qc2 $14 Qc7 13. Rac1
({More aggressive is} 13. f4 $5 $146 Rac8 14. f5 $36) 13... Rac8 14. Rfd1 a6
15. g5 Nfd7 $6 (15... Nh5 16. Nde2 $14) 16. Nd5 Qd8 17. b4 $16 {1-0 (36) Ahn,H
(2177)-Dobrovoljc,V (2334) Pardubice CZE 2019}) (10... a5 11. b3 Bd7 12. O-O
Rc8 13. Rc1 h5 14. g5 Nh7 15. h4 $16 {1-0 (38) Garcia Cardenas,P (2443)
-Guimaraes,W (2206) Sao Paulo BRA 2019}) 11. O-O Bd7 12. f4 {This is the most
ambitious continuation.} ({White is also better with more modest} 12. Qd2 Rc8
13. Rac1 $14 {1-0 (35) Zhigalko,A (2548)-Klukin,K (2325) Yekaterinburg RUS 2019
}) 12... Rc8 {[#]} {and now White has a serious improvement in} 13. e5 $1 $146
({White did not get much after} 13. Rc1 e5 14. Nb3 exf4 15. Bxf4 Nxb3 16. Qxb3
Be6 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 Re8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (96) Paszewski,M (2324)-Efimenko,Z 
(2631) Warsaw POL 2019}) 13... Ne8 14. Qe2 $1 dxe5 15. fxe5 Bxe5 16. Rad1 $36 {
with a strong pressure along the central files.}) 9. Bg2 ({Caruana's} 9. e5 Ne8
10. Bg2 Rb8 11. O-O Bb7 12. Bxb7 Rxb7 13. Qa4 {could have been neutralized with
} Nb8 (13... Nec7 14. exd6 exd6 15. Rad1 Qh4 16. Kg2 f5 17. f3 $14 {
Caruana-Adhiban, Wijk aan Zee 2018}) 14. exd6 cxd4 15. Bxd4 Nxd6 $11) 9... e5 {
This is a solid attempt to shut down g2-bishop. Black accepts a slightly worse,
but very solid closed type of position.} (9... Bb7 {is a bit more flexible,
inviting White into Benoni waters. However, the bishop will be misplaced on
that square.} 10. d5 e6 ({Black did not get enough compensation with} 10... Nc7
11. O-O a6 12. a4 Nd7 13. f4 b5 14. axb5 axb5 15. cxb5 Rxa1 16. Qxa1 Qa8 17.
Rb1 f5 18. exf5 gxf5 19. g5 Nb6 20. Qxa8 Rxa8 21. b4 $1 $16 {1-0 (43) Thybo,J 
(2525)-Ioannidis,E (2412) Skopje MKD 2019}) 11. O-O exd5 {[#] Here, I believe
that White should play go for the standard (for this line) pawn structure and
recapture} 12. exd5 $146 ({instead of} 12. cxd5 {which was rather double-edged
in the game Bernadskiy, V (2594)-Ziska, H (2533) Riga LAT 2019 1-0 (31), after:}
Nc7 13. f4 Re8 14. Qd2 b5 15. g5 Nd7 $13) 12... Nc7 13. a4 {and I don't see
how Black obtains counterplay in this position. For example, his usual} a6 {
is too slow due to} 14. Rb1 $1 Bc8 15. b4 $16) 10. d5 Nc7 11. a4 Rb8 12. Ng3 a6
13. Bf1 Bd7 14. Bd3 b5 {and here draw was agreed in the game Real de
Azua-Perez Ponsa, Villa Martelli 2018, although there is no doubt that after}
15. b3 $14 {[#] White's space advantage would give him an easier game.}) 8. Bg2
{This is one of two reasonable development schemes here.} ({GM Parligras tried
to stay true to the Makogonov system with} 8. Nge2 $5 Nc7 (8... e5 9. d5 {
would transpose to Chapter 3.}) 9. Ng3 {but Grischuk played the thematic} b5 $5
{nevertheless. After} 10. cxb5 cxb5 11. Bg2 e5 12. dxe5 dxe5 {[#]} {I believe
that White should have been more ambitious with} 13. O-O $5 $146 ({instead of} 
13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. O-O b4 15. Na4 Ne6 16. Rfd1 Bb7 $11 {Parligras-Grischuk,
Douglas 2018}) {and in this somewhat symmetrical position, I would prefer
White because of better development and chances to seize the initiative based
on the control of d5-square (g4-g5, Nc3-d5) and some weaknesses on the
queenside (a7, b5, c5, c6). Black would get a good game if he could somehow
bring his knight to d4, but it is clear from variations below that this is far
from a simple task.} 13... b4 (13... Ne6 14. Nf5 $1) 14. Nd5 Nfxd5 15. exd5 Nb5
16. Bc5) 8... e5 9. Nge2 {Of course, White avoids the blockade with his bishop
already on g2.} Nc7 {[#] This position needs more practical tests. I can
suggest two possible improvements for White over the key game
Cheparinov-Chigaev that continued 10.f4.} ({In case of} 9... exd4 {it is
important to recapture with the bishop} 10. Bxd4 $1 {[#] so that the knight
can still reach the ideal g3-square. The following game is an example of how
cramped Black position can get in this structure:} Qe7 11. O-O Nc5 {and now
the most resolute} 12. f4 $1 $146 {would have been very strong since the
e-pawn is indirectly defended} (12. Ng3 Ne6 13. Be3 Nd7 14. Qd2 a5 15. f4 $16 {
Dai-Nitin, Xingtai 2018}) {due to:} 12... Ncxe4 13. Bxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15.
Qd4+ Nf6 16. g5 $18) {The more solid one is} 10. Qd2 $5 $146 {just keeping the
tension in the position. Black is allowed to execute ...b7-b5, but White
should not be too worried about since he controls the centre.} ({A sharper
option is} 10. d5 $5 $146 cxd5 11. exd5 {[#] which strongly resembles one of
the key positions that were analyzed in Chapter 2. However, here Black has a
somewhat misplaced knight on c7 and is not as quick to push ...f7-f5. For
example, in case of} Nd7 12. g5 f5 13. gxf6 Nxf6 14. Ng3 $14 {White seems to
have all the key squares under control and comfortably castles kingside, while
Black yet has to organize some active play.}) ({Cheparinov's aggressive} 10. f4
{looks reasonable, but somehow he did not get much in the game:} exf4 11. Nxf4
Nd7 12. Qd2 b5 $1 13. cxb5 Nxb5 14. Nxb5 cxb5 15. O-O Bb7 $132 {Black seems to
be doing fine here, and the game soon ended peacefully.} 16. Rae1 a5 17. Nd5
Bxd5 18. exd5 Nb6 19. b3 b4 20. Rc1 Nc8 $1 21. Kh1 Na7 22. Qd3 Rb8 23. Bf4 Nb5
24. Rc6 Qe7 25. Bg3 {½-½ (25) Cheparinov,I-Chigaev,M Skopje 2019}) 10... b5
11. cxb5 cxb5 (11... Nxb5 12. Nxb5 cxb5 13. Ng3 $14 {also looks comfortable
for White.}) 12. a3 a5 13. O-O $14 {and I prefer White's position due to
better central control.} *

