{[%evp 0,71,14,30,25,-11,34,36,40,40,40,41,37,19,56,48,74,65,49,36,56,37,100,
62,113,102,71,22,28,-6,14,0,15,0,-8,-21,38,-15,0,-3,-2,8,8,-22,152,157,151,190,
201,201,174,199,217,194,283,351,378,388,388,498,594,594,617,715,731,815,837,
815,1497,1682,1804,2232,1551,29988]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5.
h3 O-O 6. Be3 c6 {[#] This is another flexible move for Black. He can choose
from one of several systems, depending on how White continues. The simplest
way to develop is} 7. Nf3 {when Black may try to use the position of the
knight on f3 to get a favorable version of ...Nf6-h5, ...f7-f5 plan with} Na6 {
[#] This has already been tried by some strong GMs, so it should be taken
seriously by white players, even if it is considered to be a sideline.} ({
The main alternative} 7... a6 {is covered in Chapter 11.}) {White has many
options at this point and they will be discussed below. I have a preference
for an interesting semi-waiting move} 8. Rc1 $1 {The point of this move is not
to commit the bishop to e2 for now and just do something useful while waiting
to see which plan Black will choose. Of course, like every strong opening
concept, it contains an important tactical point that disputes Black's main
idea, in this case ...Nf6-h5, ...f7-f5.} ({The most common, but not the most
precise move is} 8. Be2 {because after} e5 9. d5 Nh5 {Black achieves good play
on the kingside, as can be seen from the lines below:} 10. g3 (10. O-O Nf4 11.
Re1 Nxe2+ 12. Qxe2 f5 13. exf5 gxf5 14. Bg5 Qc7 $13) (10. Qd2 Nf4 $1 11. Bxf4
exf4 $132) (10. Nd2 Nf4 11. Bf1 f5 12. g3 Nxd5 $1 13. cxd5 f4 14. Bxa6 fxe3 15.
fxe3 bxa6 $15 {Mendonca-Ganguly, Sharjah 2019}) 10... cxd5 11. cxd5 f5 12. exf5
gxf5 13. Bg5 Nf6 $13) ({Playing in Makogonov style with} 8. g4 {has its
drawbacks here, since Black can switch plans with} Nc7 9. a4 d5 $1 $132) ({
A better way to develop the bishop is} 8. Bd3 $5 {in order to answer} e5 9. d5
Nh5 10. O-O Nf4 {with} 11. Bc2 {[#] This position was reached in a
high-profile game Anton Guijarro,D (2678)-Amin,B (2707) Changsha CHN 2019
½-½ (31). While not really threatening, the knight on f4 is mildly annoying
for White and he needs to spend several moves to expel it from there.
Meanwhile, Black obtains good counterplay on the queenside, as can be seen in
the game continuation:} Qf6 12. Kh2 Bd7 13. a3 Rfc8 14. Ng1 cxd5 15. cxd5 Qd8
16. Rc1 b5 17. g3 Nh5 18. Bd3 Qe8 19. Qe2 Nc7 $13 {with an interesting
middlegame battle.}) ({One additional idea worth mentioning is} 8. a3 e5 9. d5
Nh5 10. b4 {taking away c5-square from the black knight. However, Black had a
strong response:} c5 $1 11. Nd2 $5 {Double-edged, but it does not look like
White had any other way of preventing 11...f5.} b6 $6 ({Black should have gone
for it:} 11... cxb4 $142 12. axb4 Nxb4 13. c5 f5 $132 {with major
complications in which I would rather take Black.}) 12. Rb1 Bd7 13. g3 Be8 14.
b5 Nc7 15. Be2 $14 {Li, C-Rapport, R, Reykjavik 2014}) 8... e5 {This is the most
straightforward, though not the only continuation for Black.} ({The main
alternative is} 8... Nc7 {preparing ...b7-b5.} 9. Bd3 {This looks more active}
({than} 9. Be2 b5 (9... e5 10. d5 $14) 10. e5 dxe5 (10... Nd7 $5 $13) 11. dxe5
(11. Nxe5 $14 {Adhiban}) 11... Nd7 12. cxb5 cxb5 13. O-O $14 {Wei, Y-Adhiban,
Wijk aan Zee 2017}) 9... b5 (9... e5 {seems less logical now that Black has
already played ...Na6-c7, since after} 10. d5 Nh5 11. O-O Nf4 12. Bc2 $14 {
White may have an easier time expanding with b2-b4 and c4-c5 compared to a
similar position from the game Anton Guijarro-Amin above.}) 10. cxb5 cxb5 11.
O-O Bb7 (11... b4 12. Ne2 Ba6 13. Ng3 $16) 12. a3 a6 {[#] After a logical
opening sequence, this position was reached in the game Nguyen, A (2529)-Santos
Latasa, J (2586) Abu Dhabi UAE 2019 ½-½ (31). Instead of the game move 13.d5,
I can suggest two possible improvements:} 13. Nd2 $5 $146 {preparing to
transfer the knight to b3-square, with or without b2-b4 move (depending on
what Black does). White can also target black queenside with the move a3-a4,
while this knight manoeuvre also allows him to support his e4-pawn with f2-f3,
if need be.} ({and} 13. Qd2 $5 {preparing exchange of dark-squared bishops
with Be3-h6 in the appropriate moment. White should enjoy a slight advantage
in both cases due to a strong pawn centre and space advantage.})) ({Another
move seen in practice is} 8... Qa5 {but it is non-critical as White has more
than one way to obtain the advantage.} 9. Nd2 (9. Bd3 e5 10. O-O $14) 9... e5
10. d5 Nc5 11. a3 cxd5 12. exd5 $1 Qd8 13. b4 Ncd7 14. c5 $36 {Wei,Y-Zhao,J,
Xinghua 2016}) 9. d5 cxd5 ({The point of White's 8th move is revealed in the
critical variation:} 9... Nh5 10. Nd2 Qe8 {and now the thematic central break}
(10... Nc7 11. g3 $14) 11. c5 $3 {[#] opens up the position in White's favour:}
Nxc5 (11... f5 12. Nc4 f4 13. Nxd6 Qe7 14. Nxc8 Raxc8 15. Bd2 Nxc5 16. b4 $14)
12. Nc4 Qd8 13. dxc6 bxc6 {Here, White has a pleasant choice between a
slightly better endgame or middlegame:} 14. Nxd6 (14. Qxd6 Ne6 15. Qxd8 Rxd8
16. Na4 $14) 14... Ne6 15. Nxc8 Qxc8 16. Bc4 $14) 10. cxd5 Ne8 {Adhiban
prepares the ...f7-f5 in another way, but this allows...} 11. g4 $1 {White
eventually fulfils the strategic idea of this opening.} Kh8 {[#]} {This
critical position was reached in the game Nepomniachtchi, I-Adhiban, B Tbilisi
2017 1-0 (36). White has a clear improvement in} 12. Rg1 $1 $146 ({In the game,
White played a slightly inaccurate} 12. Be2 f5 13. gxf5 gxf5 14. exf5 Bxf5 15.
Ng5 Qe7 16. Bg4 Bh6 $1 $132 {allowing Black to obtain good counter-chances,
though he won the game in the end.}) 12... Qe7 ({The point is that after} 12...
f5 13. gxf5 gxf5 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Ng5 $36 {we get a position similar to the
game, where Rg1 is a much more useful move than Be2 for more than one reason -
as indicated in short variations below:} Qe7 (15... Bh6 16. Qh5) (15... Nf6 16.
Qf3) 16. Bd3) 13. g5 f5 14. h4 fxe4 15. Nd2 Bf5 16. Ndxe4 $14 {with a firm
control of the key e4-square and a pleasant edge.} *

