{[%evp 0,27,14,11,25,11,34,33,33,33,33,26,24,19,27,27,54,62,60,55,56,56,46,13,
29,28,30,16,57,57]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be3
Nbd7 {[#] This is a fairly rare move and probably for a good reason. It is not
as flexible as its alternatives and the knight is generally placed better on
a6 than d7. Still, Black has one interesting idea connected to ...a7-a6 (with
this move order or 6...a6 7.Nf3 Nbd7) that White should be aware of. White can
continue developing naturally with} 7. Nf3 ({Unlike in the 6...Na6 variation,
here} 7. g4 {may not be called for, since Black can organize quick counterplay
with} c5 8. Nge2 Qa5 9. Qd2 b5 $1 $132 10. cxb5 a6 11. Bg2 axb5 12. e5 cxd4 13.
Nxd4 Nxe5 14. Ncxb5 Bd7 $15 {1/2-1/2 (45) Bluebaum,M (2635)-Firouzja,A (2549)
Moscow RUS 2018}) 7... a6 {[#] Black wants to prepare the Benko gambit type of
counterplay (...c7-c5 followed by ...b7-b5) with his last move. This is the
only independent idea that White should keep in mind when facing this setup.} (
{Alternatively, Black can still go for the most common KID structure with:} 
7... e5 8. d5 {[#] which actually transposes into a branch of h3, Nf3 system
of the Makogonov after} Nc5 ({It is important that, once again,} 8... Nh5 {
does not work for Black as he would like to, in the view of:} 9. Nd2 a5 (9...
Qe8 10. Nb5 $1 {is the problem with the knight on d7 instead of a6}) 10. g3 Nc5
11. Be2 Nf6 12. g4 $14 {and, similar to Chapter 1, White usually has a promising
play on the kingside. For example:} c6 13. h4 cxd5 14. cxd5 Bd7 15. h5 $36 {
Nakamura-Amin, St Petersburg 2018}) 9. Nd2 a5 10. g4 {etc. Once again, I would
refer you to GM Marin's database on the Makogonov system in which he covered
this position in detail.}) {In this position, White has two good continuations.
The most common one is} 8. Be2 ({However, I don't think that Jakovenko's} 8.
Qc2 $5 {is any worse. The point of this prophylactic move is to overprotect
the vulnerable e4-pawn, which prevents Black's 8...c5 9.d5 b5 idea.} c6 {
If Black decides against his original idea, this is already a small victory
for White.} ({However, it is hard to see what Black can achieve by insisting on
} 8... c5 9. d5 {since} b5 $2 (9... e6 10. dxe6 fxe6 11. Rd1 $16 {
Khurtsidze-Guramishvili, Tbilisi 2013}) (9... Rb8 10. a4 $14) 10. cxb5 axb5 11.
Bxb5 $16 {simply does not work for him.}) 9. Be2 b5 10. O-O bxc4 11. Bxc4 d5
12. Bd3 dxe4 13. Nxe4 $14 {[#] After the situation in the centre has cleared
up, White can claim a small, but stable advantage due to better development of
his pieces and vulnerability of the c6-pawn.} Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Bb7 15. Rac1 Rc8
16. Qb3 Qb6 17. Qxb6 Nxb6 18. Ne5 Rfd8 19. Bxc6 $16 {and White eventually
converted the extra pawn in the endgame. Jakovenko, D-Bortnyk, O Doha 2016}) 8...
c5 9. O-O {White should keep flexibility in the centre and be ready to play a
Maroczy/Fianchetto Hedgehog type of position} ({since} 9. d5 $6 {allows Black
to obtain good counterplay with} b5 $132 {based on the following thematic
tactic:} 10. cxb5 $140 axb5 11. Bxb5 Nxe4 $1 12. Nxe4 Qa5+ 13. Nc3 Bxc3+ 14.
bxc3 Qxb5 $19) 9... cxd4 ({The following attempt will probably not repeated by
black players:} 9... b6 10. d5 b5 11. cxb5 axb5 12. Bxb5 Ba6 {Black tries to
get some sort of a Benko gambit position, but it is well-known that White gets
a clear edge against it with a4, Nb5 setup, which is exactly what GM Alonso
Rosell demonstrated in this game:} 13. Qc2 Qa5 14. a4 Rfb8 15. Nd2 Bxb5 16.
Nxb5 $16 {1-0 (29) Alonso Rosell,A (2523)-Vidarte Morales,A (2381) Barcelona
ESP 2018}) 10. Nxd4 Re8 {[#] We got a Hedgehog type of position. The last move
was necessary to prepare ...b7-b6 without having to worry about Nd4-c6
intrusion. Here, Black gets a good position if White just plays 'natural'
moves (see 11.Qd2 and 11.Qc2 below) and allows him to develop with b6, Bb7,
Qc7, e6, etc. Instead, White should act more aggressively in anticipation of
11...b6. The following new idea may put Black's setup to a serious test:} 11.
Qa4 $5 $146 {The point behind this move is to reinforce the Nd4-c6 jump in
likely case that Black plays ...b7-b6. Black seems to experience some
development problems after this move, which is evident from the lines below.} (
11. Qd2 b6 12. f3 Bb7 13. Rfd1 Rc8 14. Rac1 Nh5 $13 {0-1 (45) Ondersteijn,N 
(2415)-Markus,R (2617) Skopje MKD 2015}) (11. Qc2 b6 12. Rad1 Bb7 13. Rfe1 Rc8
14. a4 e6 15. Qb1 Qc7 16. Bf1 Qb8 $13 {0-1 (32) Van Zyl-Rudd,J (2310)
-Hamdouchi, H (2584) El Ksiba MAR 2019}) 11... b6 {This is the most natural
continuation, though it gives White an opportunity to create an outpost on c6.}
(11... Nc5 {apparently wins a tempo, but actually just exposes the knight to
the following tactical sequence:} 12. Qc2 b6 13. Bf3 $1 {We have already seen
this idea in Chapter 6.} Bb7 14. b4 Ncd7 15. e5 $1 dxe5 16. Bxb7 exd4 17. Bxd4
$16) (11... e6 {prevents Nc3-d5, but weakens d6-pawn, which can be problematic
with such a slow development.} 12. Rad1 Rb8 (12... Qc7 $2 13. Ndb5 $18) 13. b4
Qc7 14. Qc2 b6 15. b5 $1 $16) 12. Nc6 Qc7 13. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 14. cxd5 {[#] And
White should have a pleasant edge thanks to his space advantage and a strong
d5-Nc6 wedge.} Nc5 ({This whole sequence was based on the following tactic:} 
14... Bxb2 $2 15. Qc2 $1 {Otherwise, Black would be simply winning a pawn. Now
he is losing.} Bxa1 16. Nxe7+ Rxe7 17. Qxc7 $18) 15. Qc2 f5 16. exf5 Bxf5 17.
Qd2 $14 *

