{[%evp 0,35,24,20,29,-3,37,37,36,36,36,29,24,16,43,52,98,27,67,66,56,33,62,54,
49,49,49,49,62,58,50,44,67,50,50,41,38,17]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4
d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be3 {In the last chapter we look at two relatively rare, but
definitively playable options for Black. The first one is} Nc6 ({while the
second one is} 6... a6 7. Nf3 c6 {[#] This system is sometimes employed
against the Saemisch and Classical variations of the King's Indian defense.
Black prepares ...b7-b5, which not only allows him to develop his bishop to b7 
but also attack white pawn centre from the flank (bxc4 followed by ...d6-d5 or
...b5-b4, followed by ...e7-e5 are the usual ideas). The system is a bit
passive and seemingly non-threatening, but White still has to know what he is
doing, especially when it comes to reactions in the centre. The most natural
continuation is} 8. Bd3 ({but White can also be more proactive with} 8. c5 $5 {
[#] which takes some sting out of ...b7-b5. I should also mention that Black's
plan can be stopped altogether with 8.a4, and some strong players have
preferred to play this way. It is definitely a viable approach; however, I am
not sure if White needs to make a positional concession (weak b4-square) at
this stage of the game.} b5 ({It is positionally suspicious to play} 8... dxc5
$6 {considering chronic weakness of the b6-square.} 9. dxc5 Qxd1+ (9... Qa5 10.
Nd2 $16) 10. Rxd1 a5 11. Bc4 $16) (8... Nbd7 {has also been tried in practice.}
9. Qc2 ({There is also nothing wrong with} 9. Be2 $5 b5 10. cxb6 Qxb6 11. Qd2
$14 {with a likely transposition to 8...b5 line.}) 9... b5 10. Be2 dxc5 11.
dxc5 {[#] White should be slightly better in this type of position, though
Black is quite solid. However, the next move unnecessarily weakens d6-square
and makes black position problematic.} e5 $6 (11... Qc7 $142 12. O-O Nh5 13.
Rfd1 Nf4 14. Bf1 $14) 12. O-O Nh5 13. a4 $16 Bb7 14. Rfd1 Qc7 {and here in the
game Li, D (2523)-Zhao Jun (2636) Changsha CHN 2019 ½-½ (24) White could have
gained a nearly decisive advantage with a thematic piece sacrifice:} 15. axb5
axb5 16. Bxb5 $1 cxb5 17. Nxb5 Qc6 18. Nd6 Ba6 19. b4 $18) 9. cxb6 Qxb6 10. Qd2
{[#] This is another typical pawn structure that should be slightly
preferrable for White.} a5 11. Bd3 Ba6 12. O-O Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Qa6 14. Qd2 $14 {
Black managed to trade his weakest piece, but White keeps a slight edge,
nevertheless, thanks to a better pawn structure.} Nbd7 15. Bh6 e5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7
17. b3 Rad8 18. Qc2 $14 {Pavlov,S-Onischuk,V, Tsaghkadzor 2017}) 8... b5 9. O-O
bxc4 ({The other plan is} 9... Nbd7 {preparing ...e7-e5. White has many
reasonable options here, including 10.e5, but I would prefer the flexible} 10.
Qc2 $5 $146 {Black can continue developing with 10...Bb7 etc, though I think
that it is clear that White gets a nice position there in more than one way.
It is important to look at the most direct black options, such as:} e5 ({and:} 
10... bxc4 11. Bxc4 d5 12. Bd3 $14 {Interestingly, we get a transposition into
the game Jakovenko-Bortnyk from Chapter 10.}) 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13.
Rfd1 Qc7 {[#] This position resembles some positions from the Breyer
variation of the Ruy Lopez. Although Black is solid, White's position is more
pleasant since has an initiative on the queenside. Here, I like the following
knight manoeuvre:} 14. Ne2 $5 Qb8 15. Nc1 $1 $14 {planning to bring the knight
to b3 and follow it up with a2-a4, with serious pressure on black queenside.})
10. Bxc4 d5 {This is a typical clearance operation in the centre for this line.
} 11. Bd3 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Be6 {[#] Black has created an isolated
pawn on d4 for White (and consequently an outpost on d5 for his pieces), but
his own pawn structure and development are far from ideal. White had a slight
initiative in the endgame in the following GM game:} 14. Qc2 ({though I think
that Black would have to solve even more serious problems if White could keep
the queens on the board. For example:} 14. Rc1 $5 $146 Bd5 15. Bxd5 cxd5 16.
Qd2 $14 {and White's control over the c-file gives him a nice initiative.})
14... Bd5 15. Ne5 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Qd5 17. Qxd5 cxd5 18. Rfc1 $14 {0-1 (43)
Khairullin, I (2652)-Nguyen Ngoc Truong Son (2634) Berlin GER 2015}) 7. d5 {
[#] Black's provocative 6th move in the spirit of Alekhine's defence is not
without a point. He does not mind spending a tempo or two in order to provoke
White into pushing this pawn, so that he can later undermine it with ...e7-e6
or ...c7-c6 (or both). Of course, White should be able to prove an advantage
against such an 'anti-positional' approach, but surprisingly, this is not so
trivial, nor is this advantage as big as one might think. Black has three
possible knight jumps. The most serious one seems to be} Nb4 {not only because
it is the most active, but also because it was played by the World champion in
a similar position (that eventually transposes into our variation).} ({Black
can also 'lose' two full tempi with} 7... Nb8 {After} 8. Nf3 e6 9. Bd3 {
the best way to undermine white center is} exd5 (9... c6 {is less accurate
because it allows} 10. dxe6 $1 Bxe6 11. O-O $14 {with a typical pleasant edge
for White in Arnaudov,P (2441)-Petenyi,T (2449) Antalya 2017 1-0 (65)}) 10.
cxd5 c6 11. O-O cxd5 12. exd5 {[#] In general, the pawn structure with fixed
d-pawns should be better for White simply because of the extra space and more
options for his pieces. However, he should keep his d-pawn well-defended and
make sure not to trade too many pieces because with more pieces on the board,
Black eventually runs out of useful moves. His light-squared bishop is
especially limited.} Nbd7 13. Qd2 Nb6 ({Another option is} 13... Re8 14. Rfe1
a6 15. Rac1 $14 {but Black would have to think twice before developing his
bishop to b7 because 15...b5 creates a massive hole on c6 that White can
immediately target with 16.Nd4.}) 14. Bg5 $146 {This is a natural, but
important improvement over the game Pert, N (2501)-Gonzales, J (2422) Hastings
2005 ½-½ (45). I believe that White should use the battery of queen and
bishop to pin the knight without having to worry about ...h7-h6. The game
could continue} Bd7 15. Rfe1 Rc8 16. Bf1 $14 {and Black starts feeling the
lack of space. It is important that the active attempt} Nc4 {would backfire
after} 17. Qf4 Nxb2 18. Ne4 $36 {and White has a huge initiative here.}) (7...
Ne5 {is even more provocative. GM Gawain Jones showed that White need not be
shy with his pawns:} 8. g4 $1 c6 9. f4 Ned7 10. Nf3 cxd5 11. cxd5 {[#] This
position was reached in the GM game Jones, G-Pavlidis, A, Hersonissos 2017.
White controls the center fully and Black's best option is probably} b6 $146 ({
In the game, Black tried} 11... Nc5 {but after} 12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. e5 Nd7 14.
Qc2 $16 {his position was just too cramped.}) ({A clever-looking try} 11... b5
{runs into} 12. Nd4 $1 $16) 12. Bg2 Nc5 13. Qc2 Bb7 ({It is very tempting for
Black to play} 13... Ba6 {and I would imagine most people going for this in
shorter time controls, but after} 14. O-O-O $1 Rc8 15. Nd4 $16 {White is fully
in control.}) 14. O-O e6 {Black undermines white centre once again, but White
can calmly play} 15. Nd4 $1 exd5 16. exd5 Re8 17. Bf2 $14 {with an obvious
positional advantage.}) 8. Nf3 {On closer inspection, it turns out that White
is better off ignoring the knight on b4,} ({than chasing it away with} 8. a3
Na6 {The point is that this knight can quickly be rerouted to c5 from where it
attacks the key e4-square/pawn. On the other hand, it is not so clear what its
purpose is on b4. Here, White has tried to obtain an advantage with} 9. Bd3 e6
10. Nge2 (10. Nf3 {is quite harmless in the view of} Nc5 11. Bc2 exd5 12. exd5
Re8 13. O-O Nfe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bd4 Ng5 $11 {and Black neutralized White's
space advantage by trading off several pairs of pieces, in the game Garcia
Cardenas,P (2444)-Pavlidis,A (2552) Batumi 2018 ½-½ (83)}) 10... Nc5 (10...
Re8 {would allow White to take away c5-square from the knight with} 11. b4 $1
c6 12. dxc6 bxc6 13. O-O $14 {Wagner,C-Gaehler,M, Switzerland 2017}) 11. Bc2
exd5 12. cxd5 {and now in the game Kourkoulos Arditis, S (2436)-Theodorou, N 
(2543) Paleochora GRE 2019 ½-½ (36), Black could have created good
counterplay in the centre with} Re8 $146 13. f3 c6 $132) 8... e6 {This is the
right way to attack white centre because it allows Black to use the e-file
regardless of how White reacts in the centre. 8...c6 does not give him that
option.} 9. Be2 Re8 10. Nd2 $1 {[#] I believe that this is the best way for
White to keep his pawn centre intact. The fact that it was played by Levon
Aronian only solidifies this conviction. White could also play 10.0-0, but
then he would have to take back on d5 with his e-pawn. This move supports the
e4-pawn and allows him to recapture cxd5, which should give him a more
promising pawn structure.} a5 {This flexible move was Magnus Carlsen's choice.}
({In other games, Black released the tension early with} 10... exd5 11. cxd5 a5
{1-0 (59) Jimenez Ruano, A (2132)-Gutierrez Clares, J (2240) Barcelona 2016} ({
I don't think that Black is ready to play the Benoni structure after} 11... c5
12. O-O Na6 13. Re1 Nc7 14. Bf4 $16 {when White seemed to be several tempi up
compared to the usual Benoni lines in Lei, T (2436)-Zhang, X (2388) Wuxi 2014
1-0 (22)}) {and here, simply:} 12. O-O $146 Bd7 13. Re1 $14 {should give White
an edge in a slightly atypical position.}) 11. O-O Bd7 12. Re1 b6 13. Rc1 Kh8
14. a3 Na6 15. Qc2 $14 {[#] This position was reached in the top-level game
Aronian, L (2802)-Carlsen, M (2861) Wijk aan Zee 2013 ½-½ (46). White has done
well to keep his centre under control amidst Black's attempts to destabilize
it. The fact that Magnus Carlsen closed the centre on the next move proves
that White's strategy was successful.} {After:} e5 16. Rb1 Ng8 17. b4 f5 {
we got a fairly typical KID battle. Aronian had a better position throughout
the game and pretty good winning chances at some point, but Carlsen managed to
save it.} *

